"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455374","Home Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Home Department procures consultancy as a service against deliverables and outputs and not in terms of individuals. The Home Department has not terminated any consultancy service engagements early in any of the last six years and therefore has not incurred any such costs.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-02T15:27:42.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455374/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455374/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Home Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many consultants' contracts were terminated early in each of the last six years for which figures are available; and what the cost of each such termination was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455375","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Home Office has issued 3,218 publications, 93 consultations and 79 circulars since August 2012. All are published on Gov.UK.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-01T17:20:58.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455375/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455375/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Home Office: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) publications, (b) consultation documents and (c) circulars her Department has issued since August 2012; and what the title was of each such publication, consultation document or circular.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455376","Home Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>Cleaning services across the Department are outsourced and suppliers currently pay as a minimum the National Minimum Wage. From the 1 April 2016 suppliers will pay as a minimum the National Living Wage for over 25 year olds.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-03T17:31:12.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455376/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455376/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Home Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in her Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455377","Home Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The cost of Employment Tribunals can be found within the HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service annual accounts published at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/433948/hmcts-annual-report-accounts-2014-15.pdf .</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-03T17:29:25.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455377/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455377/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Home Office: Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department spent from the public purse on industrial tribunals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455378","Home Office","false","2016-03-08","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-08T16:34:48.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455378/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455378/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455378/answer/previousversion/48358","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Home Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether her Department is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455379","Home Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>The independent Crime Survey for England and Wales shows that in the year ending September 2015 violent crime was 25% lower than in June 2010 and shows no significant change compared to the previous year (September 2014). Knife crime offences recorded by the police also remain 14% below the level of offences in 2010.</p><p>Ending gang violence and exploitation is a priority for the Government and on 13 January 2016 we published a paper setting out our refreshed approach. This has a twin focus concerned with both reducing violence, including knife crime, and protecting vulnerable individuals from exploitation by gangs. We are taking a number of steps to reduce violent crime including supporting proactive policing on knife crime and working with retailers to promote the responsible sales of knives.</p><p>In addition, as part of the Government’s Serious and Organised Crime Strategy, we are funding Greater Manchester Police to deliver a project that aims to identify individuals at risk of becoming engaged in serious and organised crime and offering them an alternative path through a series of potential interventions.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-03-07T16:14:08.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455379/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455379/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Crimes of Violence: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to reduce the level of violent crime in Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","28509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455380","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>How neighbourhood policing is delivered, its priorities, and the specific model that is used, are decisions for Chief Constables in conjunction with their democratically accountable Police and Crime Commissioners. This Government believes in local policing, accountable to local communities. That is why we abolished all central Government targets and put local people in charge by introducing directly elected Police and Crime Commissioners.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-01T11:46:23.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455380/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455380/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Community Policing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police forces in England operate a neighbourhood policing model.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","28500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455381","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>Unsuccessful North Korean asylum seekers will normally be removed to South Korea. As with any other nationality, all asylum and human rights applications from North Korean nationals are carefully considered on their individual merits in accordance with our international obligations and against the background of the latest available country of origin information from a wide range of well-recognised sources.</p><p>The Constitution of Republic of Korea (South Korea) stipulates that all North Koreans are citizens of the Republic of Korea. As citizens of South Korea, North Korean asylum seekers are able to seek the protection of the South Korean authorities.</p><p>Any application for asylum owing to a fear of persecution in North Korea is, therefore, likely to fall for refusal on the basis that (i) the applicant will not be removed to North Korea. The applicant could be returned to South Korea which is not a country where they have a well founded fear of persecution; and/or (ii) the applicant could reasonably be expected to avail himself of the protection of South Korea, where they could assert citizenship.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T16:05:55.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455381/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455381/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Asylum: North Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the Government's policy is on where unsuccessful asylum applicants from North Korea are deported to.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455382","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>Legislation is in place to deal with internet trolls, cyber-stalking and cyber harassment, and perpetrators of grossly offensive, obscene or menacing behaviour. Through the Criminal Justice Act 2015, we have strengthened two communications offences which can be used to prosecute misuse of social media: section 1 of the Malicious Communications Act 1988, and section 127 of the Communications Act 2003, giving the police longer to investigate either offence, and increasing the maximum penalty for the former to two years imprisonment.</p><p>Through the UK Council for Child Internet Safety, we have brought together industry, law enforcement, academia, charities and parenting groups to work in partnership to help keep children and young people safe online.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-01T17:19:39.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455382/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455382/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Internet: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to tackle cyber harassment.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","28536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455383","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Home Office deals with thousands of cases every year and litigants frequently rely on arguments based wholly or partly on the Human Rights Act 1998. In most cases, the 1998 Act is relied on in addition to other claims. The Government Legal Department’s records do not, historically, distinguish between cases where the 1998 Act is invoked and cases where it is not. Nor do they record how many suits were settled out of court before a judgment was delivered; or how much has been paid out in such settlements. Consequently, it is not possible to provide the information requested.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-01T17:00:22.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455383/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455383/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-25","Home Office: Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many civil law suits have been brought against her Department based either wholly or partially on grounds provided by the Human Rights Act 1998; how many such suits were settled out of court before a court judgment was delivered; and how much such settlements have cost the public purse since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455384","Attorney General","false","2016-03-07","<p>The time limit for bringing proceedings for a criminal offence depends on the court in which the case can be heard. Proceedings for those offences which can only be tried in the magistrates court must usually be brought within 6 months of the alleged offence being committed. There is not usually a time limit for those offences which can only be prosecuted in the Crown Court or which can be prosecuted in either the magistrates or Crown Court. There are exceptions in relation to individual offences.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-03-07T10:39:55.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455384/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455384/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-25","Elections: Tower Hamlets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the deadline is for criminal prosecutions to be brought by the Metropolitan Police against people implicated in electoral fraud in Tower Hamlets as a result of the Election Court rulings against former mayor Lutfur Rahman.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","28599"
