"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455390","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-02","<p>The UK remains committed to a long term partnership with Afghanistan, as I communicated to President Ghani when I visited in June 2015.</p><p>It is worth noting that Afghanistan has made significant progress over the last decade, and the UK will continue our support to protect these hard-won gains. For example, UK support has helped ensure that more than 60% of the population now live within 2 hours walking distance of public health facilities, compared to only 9% in 2002. We have committed to spend £178m million in bilateral aid per year until at least 2017, and future commitments will be determined as part of the Bilateral Aid Review, due to be published shortly.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-02T17:06:56.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455390/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455390/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Afghanistan: Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of planned budget changes to her Department's Afghanistan Project on economic security in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","28510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455391","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-02","<p>In the last 12 month period DFID has spent £84.30 on Industrial Tribunals.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-02T16:39:56.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455391/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455391/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Department for International Development: Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department spent from the public purse on industrial tribunals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455392","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-02","<p>DFID has 2 headquarters in the UK, one in Whitehall and one in East Kilbride. The cleaning of both headquarter buildings is contracted out to MITIE Facilities Management. MITIE pay the cleaning staff the National Living wage in East Kilbride and the London Living wage in Whitehall.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-02T16:42:20.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455392/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455392/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Department for International Development: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in her Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455393","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-03","<p>All such materials can be found on the GOV.UK website, in line with our commitment to transparency which saw us ranked second globally in the 2014 Aid Transparency Index.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-03T16:29:05.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455393/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455393/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Department for International Development: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many (a) publications, (b) consultation documents and (c) circulars her Department has issued since August 2012; and what the title was of each such publication, consultation document or circular.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455394","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-02","<p>DFID does not hold specific information relating to termination of consultants’ contracts.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-02T16:43:05.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455394/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455394/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Department for International Development: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many consultants' contracts were terminated early in each of the last six years for which figures are available; and what the cost of each such termination was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455395","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Brussels Conference on Afghanistan in October 2016 will consider progress against the Self Reliance through the Mutual Accountability Framework agreed between the National Unity Government and the international community in September 2015. This Framework includes an objective to improve the investment climate and a commitment on the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative (EITI).</p><p> </p><p>Responsible development of the extractives sector is a UK priority. We are supporting the Government to strengthen legal frameworks, contract management and fiscal regimes, and to implement the Extractives Industries Transparency Initiative.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-01T17:09:12.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455395/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455395/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Afghanistan: Mining","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the UK is intending to take steps to ensure that effective benchmarks for extractive-sector governance are included on the agenda for the Brussels Conference on Afghanistan.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","28435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455396","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>The UK proposed changes to the Minerals Law as part of a review commissioned by the Afghan Ministry of Mines and Petroleum in 2015; and supported the incorporation of recommendations from donors and transparency organisations into amendments. The Mining Advisory Council is reviewing the amendments before submission to the Ministry of Justice.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-01T17:08:19.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455396/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455396/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Afghanistan: Minerals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department has taken to ensure that the Afghan Minerals Law includes the strongest possible measures to strengthen transparency and reduce the risk of corruption in the Afghan extractive sector.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","28431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455397","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>The British Embassy regularly consults the National Unity Government on improving the Minerals Law to encourage responsible investment into the extractives sector. The UK proposed revisions to the Minerals Law in a review commissioned by the Ministry of Mines and Petroleum and provided support for the incorporation of recommendations by transparency organisations and donor partners into amendments.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-01T17:08:33.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455397/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455397/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-25","Afghanistan: Minerals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what political representations UK officials have made to the Afghan government with respect to the Afghan Minerals Law and amendments currently being considered by the Afghan government; and whether UK officials have provided technical assistance in the preparation of those amendments.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","28432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455398","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-14","<p><strong>Table A:</strong> Annual cost (July to June) of providing advocacy services at each Secure Training Centre (STC) from July 2010 to June 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>YEAR</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>STC</strong></p></td><td><p>Jul 2010 - Jun 2011</p></td><td><p>Jul 2011 - Jun 2012</p></td><td><p>Jul 2012 - Jun 2013</p></td><td><p>Jul 2013 - Jun 2014</p></td><td><p>Jul 2014 - Jun 2015</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Medway STC</p></td><td><p>£54k</p></td><td><p>£53k</p></td><td><p>£53k</p></td><td><p>£34k</p></td><td><p>£34k</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oakhill STC</p></td><td><p>£38k</p></td><td><p>£45k</p></td><td><p>£45k</p></td><td><p>£33k</p></td><td><p>£33k</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rainsbrook STC</p></td><td><p>£40k</p></td><td><p>£46k</p></td><td><p>£46k</p></td><td><p>£35k</p></td><td><p>£35k</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hassockfield STC</p></td><td><p>£63k</p></td><td><p>£50k</p></td><td><p>£50k</p></td><td><p>£32k</p></td><td><p>£20k</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Totals</strong></p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>£195k</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>£194k</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>£194k</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>£134k</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>£122k</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>- Costs in the table have been rounded to the nearest £ ‘000</p><p>- Due to rounding, the sum of the costs for each individual STC may not match the overall total line in the table.</p><p>- Due to the cost years running from July to June, the information for July 2015-June 2016 has not been included as this would only be a partial cost for the year.</p><p> </p><p>In July 2013 the Youth Justice Board (YJB) awarded a new advocacy contract across all secure training centres. Barnardos won both parts. The annual cost of the advocacy service at each secure training centre reduced as a result of them being able to make efficiency savings from back office functions. There was no reduction in service.</p><p> </p><p>The lower advocacy costs for Hassockfield STC between July 2014 and June 2015 are a result of the site being decommissioned in 2014. The advocacy service ceased on 21 November 2014.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-14T16:53:09.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455398/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455398/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Secure Training Centres: Advocacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the annual cost was of the advocacy contract at each secure training centre in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455399","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>A total annual cost of the Youth Justice Board’s (YJB) monitoring of each Secure Training Centre provided by the YJB is not held centrally.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-01T14:44:06.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455399/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455399/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Secure Training Centres: Monitoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the annual cost was of the Youth Justice Board monitoring carried out at each secure training centre in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455400","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-30","<p>The relevant termination costs are subject to ongoing commercial discussions. We have spent approximately £21m on programme mobilisation to date. The majority of this was spent on investment in the telecommunications network, mapping software, monitoring service and other programme costs which the MoJ will be able to reuse for ongoing electronic monitoring work.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-30T15:22:18.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455400/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455400/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Ministry of Justice: Steatite","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Written Statement by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Justice, 25 February 2016, HCWS549, on offender management, what financial penalties were incurred by his Department as a result of terminating the contract to develop a bespoke tagging product with Steatite Limited; and how much his Department spent on that contract before its termination.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455401","Ministry of Justice","true","2016-03-04","<p>The safety and welfare of young people in custody is vital and we take all incidents of violence extremely seriously.</p><p> </p><p>A pilot of Body Worn Video Cameras (BWVCs) is currently taking place across <del class="ministerial">24</del><ins class="ministerial">23</ins> prisons, including Cookham Wood, Feltham and Wetherby under -18 Young Offender Institutions.</p><p> </p><p>BWVCs are already in use at all Secure Training Colleges (STCs).</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-04T14:50:06.627Z","2016-03-07T14:22:46.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455401/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455401/answer","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455401/answer/previousversion/49267","Biography information for Andrew Selous","54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Youth Custody: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make it his Department's policy that all prison officers in youth facilities should wear body-mounted cameras.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455402","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>Yes. All young people have the opportunity to speak with a Barnardos advocate without a member of the Secure Training Centre staff being present. Both advocates and monitors can also speak to children confidentially without Secure Training Centre staff being present.</p><p> </p><p>Young people can also contact an advocate directly by calling their helpline number, which is free and available to all children to call in privacy from their rooms.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-01T16:53:18.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455402/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455402/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Medway Secure Training Centre: Advocacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether Barnardo's advocates are permitted to speak to children confidentially without G4S staff in attendance at Medway Secure Training Centre.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455403","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-04T11:48:56.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455403/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455403/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Ministry of Justice: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many consultants' contracts were terminated early in each of the last six years for which figures are available; and what the cost of each such termination was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455404","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>I am unable to provide the data you have requested within the timescales for this parliamentary question. I will write to you in due course with such data as officials can collate from casework systems.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-02T12:07:37.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455404/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455404/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average number of months has been between the tariff expiry date of prisoners (a) with life sentences and (b) imprisoned for public protection and the date of their first release by the Parole Board in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","28566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455405","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>We publish consultations and other publications on GOV.UK. The list of pages published is available through a filtered search. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=all&amp;topics%5b%5d=all&amp;departments%5b%5d=ministry-of-justice&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5b%5d=all&amp;from_date=01%2F08%2F2012&amp;to_date" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=all&amp;topics[]=all&amp;departments[]=ministry-of-justice&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations[]=all&amp;from_date=01%2F08%2F2012&amp;to_date</a>=</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-04T14:09:29.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455405/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455405/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Ministry of Justice: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) publications, (b) consultation documents and (c) circulars his Department has issued since August 2012; and what the title was of each such publication, consultation document or circular.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455406","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Prime Minister told the house on 3 February that the Governments position is that the EU should not join the European Convention on Human Rights. We are committed in our manifesto to change Britain’s relationship with respect to the European Court of Human Rights through our own British Bill of Rights. We shall be coming up with proposals for that shortly.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-01T16:59:46.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455406/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455406/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 27179, whether the requirement in the Lisbon Treaty that the EU shall accede to the European Convention on Human Rights is legally enforceable.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","28590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455407","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>Each year the Prison Service Pay Review Body (PSPRB) considers evidence from both NOMS and remit group trade unions (PCS, the POA and the PGA), then makes pay recommendations which are independent of all parties as well as wider Government. I have met with NOMS officials and POA officials separately and together on a number of occasions.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-04T11:44:53.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455407/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455407/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Prison Officers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with (a) NOMS and (b) the Prison Officers Association on evidence submitted to the Prison Service Pay Review Body on rates of pay for prison officers.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","28563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455408","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>The information you have requested in respect of the number of indeterminate sentence prisoners (ie those prisoners serving a life sentence or an indeterminate sentence of Imprisonment for Public Protection - IPP) who have been recalled in each year since 2005 is available in the Ministry of Justice’s offender management quarterly statistical bulletin. This can be found using the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly</a></p><p>The figures in these tables have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p><p>We are unable to provide the data on the average amount of time indeterminate sentence prisoners spend in custody following recall and before their re-release. Whilst this information is held on individual case files, the NOMS electronic case management system is unable to provide a report on the average period of time spent. In order to provide an answer it would be necessary to undertake a manual exercise looking at the case records of all indeterminate sentence prisoners during this period. Such an exercise would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","28568","2016-03-04T14:23:51.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455408/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455408/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners serving life sentences have been recalled to custody in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","28567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455409","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>Cleaning services within the Ministry of Justice are typically undertaken by outsourced providers. Cleaners working within Ministry of Justice sites are therefore employed directly by these outsourced providers or their subcontractors and/or agencies.</p><p> </p><p>Rates of pay for cleaners are determined by their respective employers and not held by the Ministry of Justice. All employers are obligated to pay at least the National Minimum Wage and the new National Living Wage from April 2016.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-04T11:59:35.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455409/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455409/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Ministry of Justice: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455410","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>The cost of Employment Tribunals can be found within the HMCTS annual accounts published at<em>: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/433948/hmcts-annual-report-accounts-2014-15.pdf.</em></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-03-02T12:57:47.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455410/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455410/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Ministry of Justice: Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department spent from the public purse on industrial tribunals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455411","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>I have no plans to do so. It is irresponsible for any campaign group to criticise our proposals before they've seen them. Amnesty have already been told our plans involve the UK remaining in the European Convention.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-01T16:51:50.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455411/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455411/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Amnesty International","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to respond to the findings of Amnesty International UK's Annual Report, published on 24 February 2016.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455412","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>As the Secretary of State has said, the prison estate is overcrowded and out of date. That’s why we have announced that we will close down aging and ineffective prisons, replacing them with new facilities fit for the modern world.</p><p> </p><p>We are investing £1.3 billion to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation. In our new prisons we will design out those features that facilitate bullying, drug-taking and violence.</p><p> </p><p>We are also constructing a modern 2,106 place prison, HMP Berwyn, in North Wales, that will be opened in 2017 and are building two new house-blocks at existing prison sites Stocken and Rye Hill.</p><p> </p><p>We remain committed to ensuring that there are enough places for offenders sentenced to custody by the courts and making sure that these places are safe, decent and secure.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-02T12:17:02.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455412/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455412/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Prisons: Overcrowding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department has taken to reduce overcrowding on the prison estate in England and Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","28486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455413","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>It is not possible to provide the information requested. Litigants in civil cases can rely on arguments based wholly or partly on the Human Rights Act 1998. In some cases, the Act is relied on in addition to other claims. When the Human Rights Act came into force, no specific arrangements were put in place by the then government to record cases in the way requested. As a result, there are not currently data published which distinguish between cases where the Human Rights Act was or was not invoked.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-04T12:09:00.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455413/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455413/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Ministry of Justice: Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many civil law suits have been brought against his Department based either wholly or partially on grounds provided by the Human Rights Act 1998; how many such suits were settled out of court before a court judgment was delivered; and how much such settlements have cost the public purse since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455414","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>The information you have requested in respect of the number of indeterminate sentence prisoners (ie those prisoners serving a life sentence or an indeterminate sentence of Imprisonment for Public Protection - IPP) who have been recalled in each year since 2005 is available in the Ministry of Justice’s offender management quarterly statistical bulletin. This can be found using the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly</a></p><p>The figures in these tables have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p><p>We are unable to provide the data on the average amount of time indeterminate sentence prisoners spend in custody following recall and before their re-release. Whilst this information is held on individual case files, the NOMS electronic case management system is unable to provide a report on the average period of time spent. In order to provide an answer it would be necessary to undertake a manual exercise looking at the case records of all indeterminate sentence prisoners during this period. Such an exercise would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","28567","2016-03-04T14:23:51.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455414/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455414/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what average number of months life-sentenced prisoners who were recalled to custody in the last five years spent in prison before they were re-released.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","28568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455415","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Department publishes overtime payment data on a monthly basis and the report can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/workforce-management-information-moj" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/workforce-management-information-moj</a></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-04T11:56:06.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455415/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455415/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-25","Ministry of Justice: Overtime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department has paid to staff in overtime in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455416","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>My Department directly employs one Band F cleaner whose rate of pay is between £15,440-£16,000 per year. We also have a contract with Serco to provide cleaners at an hourly rate of £7.65. These cleaners all work in our Belfast office.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-03-02T15:27:37.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455416/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455416/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-25","Northern Ireland Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in her Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455417","Prime Minister","false","2016-03-01","<p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p>The civil service is working full-time to support the Government’s position. A document setting out the principal alternatives to our membership of the EU will be published shortly.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-03-01T17:55:41.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455417/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455417/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-02-25","Prime Minister: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, with reference to his Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether his Office is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455418","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-01","<p>As part of the Government’s ongoing review of noise and airspace policies it will consider the proposals set out the Aviation Environment Federation’s letter to the Prime Minister of 18 February.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-01T15:27:04.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455418/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455418/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Prime Minister will make an assessment of the potential merits of each proposal on noise mitigation from aviation in the letter to him of 18 February 2016 from the Aviation Environment Federation.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455419","Scotland Office","false","2016-03-10","<p>For cleaning services the Scotland Office uses contracts through frameworks held by the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government. The Scotland Office does not set the wages paid by the contractors to its workers. Both contractors pay the national minimum wage, £6.70 per hour. From April, both contractors will increase their rate of pay to £7.20 in line with the new national minimum wage.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-03-10T11:38:01.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455419/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455419/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-02-25","Scotland Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455420","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2016-03-07","<p>The Electoral Commission works with the National Police Chiefs’ Council to collate data from police forces about cases of alleged electoral fraud reported each year. This data is published on the Commission’s website.</p><p>The data show that 49 cases of alleged electoral fraud offences were reported in Tower Hamlets in 2014. Of these cases, no further action was taken following investigation by the police in 39 cases. This was either because the activity involved was not in fact an offence; there was no evidence that an offence had been committed; or there was insufficient evidence to identify a perpetrator. It also included cases which, following investigation, were found not to have involved electoral fraud offences.</p><p>Five cases were locally resolved with advice from the police or the Returning Officer, and one case resulted in a caution being given. Of the remaining four cases, one resulted in court proceedings being initiated, one awaits prosecution advice and two remain under investigation.</p><p>A total of 28 cases of alleged electoral fraud offences were reported in Tower Hamlets in 2015. No further action was taken following investigation by the police in 23 cases, and one case was locally resolved. One case awaits prosecution advice and three remain under investigation. The Commission will monitor the outcome of any investigations relating to electoral fraud offences.</p><p>In advance of the May 2016 elections, the Commission is working closely with the police and electoral administrators in each of the 18 areas it has identified as being at higher risk of allegations of electoral fraud, including Tower Hamlets, to ensure that robust plans are in place to detect and prevent fraud.</p><p>The Commission also encourages anyone who has evidence that an electoral offence may have been committed to report this to the police, either directly or anonymously through Crimestoppers.</p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2016-03-07T12:12:41.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455420/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455420/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2016-02-25","Elections: Tower Hamlets","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what recent assessment the Commission has made of the level of electoral fraud in Tower Hamlets.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","28597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455421","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The safeguards that are in place to protect information held by the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) vary depending on the channel used and sensitivity of the data processed through the service.</p><p> </p><p>All the DVLA’s information systems and electronic services are subject to a formal assessment before they are made available to the public. This ensures that there are adequate policies, procedural and technical controls in place to protect the data.</p><p> </p><p>Privacy Impact Assessments are also completed to identify and address any privacy risks associated with the service and ensure that personal data is processed in compliance with the Data Protection Act 1998.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-03T17:02:52.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455421/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455421/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what safeguards are in place to protect information held by the DVLA on those who use its services.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","28579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455422","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The information requested is not available without disproportionate cost, as separate records for cases based wholly or partially on the Human Rights Act 1998 are not maintained.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T16:15:03.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455422/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455422/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Department for Transport: Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many civil law suits have been brought against his Department based either wholly or partially on grounds provided by the Human Rights Act 1998; how many such suits were settled out of court before a court judgment was delivered; and how much such settlements have cost the public purse since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455423","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-01","<p>The formal accident investigation into the loss of the Metrojet flight over Sinai on 31 October 2015 has not formally reached any conclusions as to the cause of the crash. But the Russian authorities announced, in November 2015, their conclusion that the aircraft was brought down by an explosive device, and the Government have been proceeding on that basis.</p><p> </p><p>The incident highlights the importance for airports, airlines and countries to increase vigilance and make sure that sound security measures are in place. The Government is working to ensure this happens, but does not discuss the details of security arrangements.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-01T15:29:19.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455423/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455423/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Aviation: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the implications for his future policies of the Sharm el Sheikh air crash in October 2015; and what recent reports he has received on the reasons for that crash.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28596"
