p>£1,339,767</p></td><td><p>£1,290,854</p></td><td><p>£1,403,393</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Month</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Aug-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Sep-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Oct-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Nov-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Dec-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Jan-16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Overtime spend</strong></p></td><td><p>£888,400</p></td><td><p>£911,069</p></td><td><p>£1,051,989</p></td><td><p>£775,587</p></td><td><p>£357,148</p></td><td><p>£446,784</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Both the twelve month periods shown above - February 2014 to January 2015 and February 2015 to January 2016 - show a reduction in overtime spend compared to the first twelve-month period of the Coalition government in 2010/11.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T16:40:53.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455424/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455424/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Department for Transport: Overtime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has paid to staff in overtime in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455425","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>Accessible on-board information helps a wide range of passengers, including those who are visually impaired, to feel comfortable and confident when taking the bus.</p><p> </p><p>Traditionally however, systems providing automatic next stop announcements have proven expensive to fit and maintain, meaning that mandating their use would place a disproportionate financial burden on the bus industry.</p><p> </p><p>My Department has supported initiatives to develop innovative and low-cost approaches to providing such information, as well as providing Better Bus Area funding for local authority schemes to equip vehicles with audio/visual equipment.</p><p> </p><p>Many operators are already recognising the benefits of on-board information for all their customers, and I would encourage others to do the same.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-03T17:06:02.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455425/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455425/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Bus Services: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if it will make it his policy to require bus operators to install audio-visual announcements of bus stops on all public buses.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","28574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455426","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The hourly rate of pay for cleaners directly employed by the Department for Transport is £8.94.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T17:11:39.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455426/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455426/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Department for Transport: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455427","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The cost of Employment Tribunals can be found within the HMCTS annual accounts published at<em>: </em></p><p><em> </em></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/433948/hmcts-annual-report-accounts-2014-15.pdf" target="_blank"><em>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/433948/hmcts-annual-report-accounts-2014-15.pdf</em></a><em>.</em></p><p><em> </em></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T16:06:47.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455427/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455427/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Department for Transport: Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department spent from the public purse on industrial tribunals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455428","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Department for Transport publishes its publications, consultations and circulars on GOV.UK. Details of individual publications published since August 2012 can be found by searching GOV.UK for DfT publications and consultations: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-transport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;from_date=31%2F07%2F2012&amp;to_date" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-transport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;from_date=31%2F07%2F2012&amp;to_date</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T16:23:54.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455428/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455428/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Department for Transport: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) publications, (b) consultation documents and (c) circulars his Department has issued since August 2012; and what the title was of each such publication, consultation document or circular.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455429","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T17:08:37.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455429/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455429/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Department for Transport: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many consultants' contracts were terminated early in each of the last six years for which figures are available; and what the cost of each such termination was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455430","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>In November 2015, the Secretary of State for Transport provided an update to Parliament on our progress to deliver HS2. He reconfirmed the Government’s commitment to completing the full Y-shaped network by 2033. The Government will make a decision on the remainder of the Phase Two route, including the Eastern Leg, in autumn 2016, with a view to introducing a third hybrid Bill before the end of this Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T16:59:55.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455430/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455430/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to bring forward legislative proposals to enable the construction of the Eastern Leg of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","28548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455431","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Walk to School programme funded by the Local Sustainable Transport Fund achieved significant modal shift: in primary schools the number of pupils walking all or part of the way to school increased by 23% and the number being driven all the way decreased by 30%. In secondary schools the number of pupils walking increased by 12%. These new walking journeys, many of which were converted from car, resulted in considerable transport and health benefits.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T17:26:45.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455431/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455431/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Pupils: Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the walk to school programme on (a) children's health and (b) reducing traffic congestion.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455432","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>My Department has launched a £20 million Sustainable Travel Transition Year Fund revenue competition for 2016/17, which local authorities are invited to bid for. This provides an opportunity to fund initiatives that support children walking to school. Information about bidding can be found on the DfT website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sustainable-travel-transition-year-revenue-competition-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sustainable-travel-transition-year-revenue-competition-2016-to-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>From 2017/18 the new Access fund will provide another opportunity for local investment in walking to schools; £500 million of capital funding will be made available for this as part of the Local Growth Fund with a further £60 million of revenue funding to be made available by my Department.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This Government has introduced a requirement to set a Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy, which will be published in 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T17:15:17.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455432/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455432/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Pupils: Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department plans to take to increase the number of children walking to school once the Local Sustainable Transport Fund ends.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455433","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>Since 2013 the Department has worked with the Department of Health (DH) to deliver projects to increase walking levels in Norwich, Birmingham, Cambridge, Greater Manchester and Leeds/Bradford through DH funded Walking Cities programme. These projects have now started to achieve a cultural and strategic shift towards more walkable cities which complements the Department’s investment in measures to increase cycling levels through the Cycle Ambition Cities programme.</p><p> </p><p>A report and evaluation summary of the interventions in Birmingham, Leeds/Bradford and Norwich reveals that 49% were more likely to choose walking and 47% felt fit and healthy as a result of being involved in the programme. The five Cities in receipt of Walking City funding have highlighted the need for capital funding to deliver infrastructure improvements to make walking safer and easier to support increased walking levels.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T17:17:50.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455433/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455433/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Department of Health to encourage more people to walk.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455434","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Walk to school programme funded by the Local Sustainable Transport Fund achieved significant modal shift: in primary schools the number of pupils walking all or part of the way to school increased by 23% and the number being driven all the way decreased by 30%. In secondary schools the number of pupils walking increased by 12%.</p><p> </p><p>Modal shift data collected from the programme, alongside various other actual and estimated figures, indicated that the project produced over 20 million new walking journeys, and took over 18.5 million car miles off the road network.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T17:21:01.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455434/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455434/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Pupils: Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the walk to school programme on the Government's objective to increase the proportion of children aged five to 10 that usually walk to school from 46 per cent in 2013 to 55 per cent in 2025.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455435","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong> </strong>The following number of incidents of involving laser pens and trains has been recorded over the last 5 years:-</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>81</p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>64</p></td><td><p>59</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-03T16:45:21.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455435/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455435/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Railways: Lasers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many incidents of laser pen attacks were recorded on trains in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","28440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455436","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>Highways England do not keep specific records of laser pen attacks. However, their records currently show that one incident involved the use of a laser pen.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-03T16:48:57.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455436/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455436/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-25","Motor Vehicles: Lasers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many incidents of laser pen attacks were recorded on road vehicles in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","28441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455437","Wales Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>Cleaning services within the Wales Office are undertaken by outsourced providers under Ministry of Justice contracts.</p><p> </p><p>Rates of pay for cleaners are determined by their respective employers and not held by the Wales Office or Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p><p>All employers are obligated to pay at least the National Minimum Wage and the new National Living Wage from April 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-03-04T14:30:52.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455437/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455437/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-02-25","Wales Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455438","Department for Education","false","2016-03-04","<p>The hourly rate of pay for cleaners working in buildings managed by the Department for Education is between £7.85 and £9.15 depending on location and duration of tenure.</p><p>The Government Equality Office is based within buildings managed by the Department for Education, and therefore the same rates apply.</p><p>From 1 April 2016, the rate of pay will be increased to the 2016 Living Wage Foundation rates.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","28602","2016-03-04T12:48:54.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455438/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455438/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-25","Department for Education: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in the Government Equalities Office.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455439","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-04","<p>Since 1998 the Department for Work and Pensions has outsourced the provision and maintenance for the majority of its estate to Telereal Trillium under a 20 year Private Finance Initiative (PFI) contract that expires on 31 March 2018.</p><p>Under the terms of the contract, Telereal Trillium provides fully-serviced accommodation, for which we pay an all-inclusive annual charge. Engie are Telereal Trillium’s cleaning service provider.</p><p>The Engie base rate of pay for all cleaners within the M25 is £9.15 (London Living Wage) which will increase to the new London Living Wage of £9.40 by May 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Engie base rate of pay for all cleaners outside the M25 is £6.70 (or the scale appropriate to their age) which will change in April 2016 to the National Living Wage of £7.20 (or the scale appropriate to their age).</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-04T14:11:21.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455439/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455439/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-25","Department for Work and Pensions: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455440","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-04","<p>The cost of Employment Tribunals can be found within the HMCTS annual accounts published at<em>:</em></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/433948/hmcts-annual-report-accounts-2014-15.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/433948/hmcts-annual-report-accounts-2014-15.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided the link to the previous full financial year rather than the last 12 months of operation as the most recent 12 months of data has not been audited and does not contain the full overhead costs which are only applied at the end of the financial year and, as such, will not provide a like-for-like comparison with published data in prior years.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-04T13:50:30.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455440/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455440/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-25","Department for Work and Pensions: Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department spent from the public purse on industrial tribunals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28632"
