"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454772","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-02","<p>The information requested can be obtained from “National Infrastructure Pipeline”, published in July 2015 and is available here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-infrastructure-pipeline-july-2015</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","28196 ; 28202","2016-03-02T16:49:43.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454772/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454772/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Infrastructure: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of national infrastructure investment has been allocated to projects in (a) Stoke-on-Trent local authority, (b) Cheshire East local authority, (c) the West Midlands region, (d) the South East region and (e) London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454773","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>As we have said previously, this government will be spending twice as much in cash terms on apprenticeships by 2020 compared to 2010. Spending on apprenticeships in England will be £2.5bn in 2019-20. The BIS spending review settlement for apprenticeships reflects the government’s commitment regarding the proceeds of the Libor fine the FCA announced in April 2015. Further announcements that support the government’s commitment to delivering employment opportunities for young people will be announced in due course.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","28354","2016-02-29T16:29:02.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454773/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454773/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Deutsche Bank: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 12 February 2016 to Question 25976, whether the proceeds from the £227 million fine imposed on Deutsche Bank will be specifically applied to a new new three-year fund to create 50,000 apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","28353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454774","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-02","<p>The government is committed to supporting the British gin industry. The duty on gin was cut by 2% at March Budget 2015, building on the duty freeze at Budget 2014.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-03-02T16:50:58.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454774/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454774/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Gin","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to support the British gin industry.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","28412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454775","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>As we have said previously, this government will be spending twice as much in cash terms on apprenticeships by 2020 compared to 2010. Spending on apprenticeships in England will be £2.5bn in 2019-20. The BIS spending review settlement for apprenticeships reflects the government’s commitment regarding the proceeds of the Libor fine the FCA announced in April 2015. Further announcements that support the government’s commitment to delivering employment opportunities for young people will be announced in due course.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","28353","2016-02-29T16:29:02.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454775/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454775/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Deutsche Bank: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 12 February 2016 to Question 25976, what discussions his officials have had with their counterparts in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on the mechanisms for implementing the Prime Minister's commitment of April 2015 to use the proceeds from the £227 million fine imposed on Deutsche Bank to create a new three-year fund to create 50,000 apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","28354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454776","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility does not provide a forecast for net UK contributions to EU budgets, and does not take into account receipts directly received by the private sector.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-29T17:06:42.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454776/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454776/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the net annual UK financial contribution to the EU is expected to be in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","28349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454777","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Dorneywood estate is the responsibility of the Dorneywood Trust. As such the Government does not hold details of redecoration or repairs to the estate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","28251","2016-02-29T16:40:59.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454777/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454777/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Dorneywood: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many times Dorneywood has been redecorated in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454778","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Dorneywood estate is the responsibility of the Dorneywood Trust. As such the Government does not hold details of redecoration or repairs to the estate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","28331","2016-02-29T16:40:59.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454778/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454778/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Dorneywood: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much public money has been spent on repairs to Dorneywood in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454779","Church Commissioners","false","2016-02-29","<p>A formal claim for compensation was submitted in April 2014 and was settled in the autumn of 2015. The settlement followed a thorough pre-litigation process during which investigations took place.</p><p>Following the settlement of the claim the Bishop of Chichester, the Rt Revd Martin Warner issued a formal apology. The statement can be read on the Church of England’s website at the following address: <a href="https://www.churchofengland.org/media-centre/news/2015/10/statement-on-the-rt-revd-george-bell-%281883-1958%29.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.churchofengland.org/media-centre/news/2015/10/statement-on-the-rt-revd-george-bell-%281883-1958%29.aspx</a></p><p>The statement from Bishop Warner went on to say that “the response from the Diocese of Chichester in 1995, when the survivor first came forward, fell a long way short, not just of what is expected now, but of what we now appreciate you should have had a right to expect then.&quot;</p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-02-29T16:22:30.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454779/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454779/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-02-24","George Bell","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, whether the settlement the Church Commissioners made to the complainant against George Bell was made directly in relation to allegations against Bell, or on the basis that a complaint made under a subsequent Bishop, was not handled in a way which would be expected today.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","28341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454780","Church Commissioners","false","2016-02-29","<p>The language of “guilt” and “charge sheets” refers to criminal cases. The claim against Bishop Bell was a civil claim. The civil courts do not use charge sheets and as a result there has not been a charge sheet for the Estates Commissioners to see then or now.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-02-29T16:23:38.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454780/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454780/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-02-24","George Bell","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, whether any of the Estates Commissioners saw the charge sheet on which George Bell was found guilty of child abuse on the balance of probabilities.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","28342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454781","Church Commissioners","true","2016-02-29","<p><ins class="ministerial">In 2013 and 2015 three staff members viewed various sections of the bishop's personal papers held at</ins> Lambeth Palace Library <ins class="ministerial">on two separate occasions.</ins> <del class="ministerial">has no record in the last three years of any of the individuals involved in these investigations making an application to view the papers and diaries of George Bell that are held in the Library.</del></p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-02-29T16:24:51.197Z","2016-05-06T09:26:14.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454781/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454781/answer","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454781/answer/previousversion/47893","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-02-24","George Bell","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, how many people involved in investigating allegations of child abuse made against George Bell consulted his papers and diaries in Lambeth Palace Library in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","28343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454782","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>This information is available on the Government website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-council-tax" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-council-tax</a></p><p>The table shows that the average levels of Band D council tax (including parish precepts) in those years are:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>£1,468</p></td><td><p>£1,484</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hertfordshire<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>£1,380 - £1,516</p></td><td><p>£1,402 - £1,539</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stevenage</p></td><td><p>£1,455</p></td><td><p>£1,477</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>1: Range from lowest (Broxbourne) to highest (Watford)</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:12:04.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454782/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454782/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 21 January 2016 to Question 23515, what estimate he has made of the total cost to people who pay council tax of that tax in (a) Stevenage, (b) Hertfordshire and (c) England in (i) 2014-15 and (ii) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","28259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454783","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>Young people’s eligibility for support with their housing costs is set out in the relevant benefit regulations.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:10:03.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454783/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454783/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Housing: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 26584, on housing: young people, what conditions vulnerable young people have to meet in order to qualify as being in need of support.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","28241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454784","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>During the passage of the then Cities and Devolution Bill we undertook to review the legislation on the disqualification of local authority members and to consult on proposals for change to bring the legislative rules into line with modern sentencing guidelines. Our intention is to launch the consultation as soon as practicable this year.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:07:27.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454784/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454784/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Councillors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to ensure that people who have been convicted of a child sex offence cannot serve as a local authority or parish councillor.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","28306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454785","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The non-statutory guidelines available to the First-tier Tribunal (Property Chamber) when considering applications for statutory recognition of a tenants' association, apply to all residential blocks of flats, large or small.</p><p>Recognising concerns raised about the ability to acquire statutory recognition, the Department published a detailed discussion paper last year to consider what more can be done through the existing guidelines to assist the tribunal when considering applications. We are currently considering responses to the discussion paper.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:26:59.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454785/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454785/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Tenants' Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent consideration he has given to amending existing non-statutory guidelines on Residential Leasehold and Recognised Tenants' Associations to ensure that those who reside in larger blocks and developments have the same opportunity to gain recognition as a recognised tenants' association as those in smaller blocks and developments.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","28333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454786","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Department does not assess the potential contribution that individual classes of organisation, including Community Land Trusts, can make to the delivery of affordable housing. However, we recognise the role they can play in delivering locally led and innovative housing development and we are confident they will make a valuable contribution to the 400,000 affordable housing starts we have committed to deliver by 2021.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:26:08.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454786/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454786/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Community Land Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential contribution of community land trusts to increasing the supply of affordable housing in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454787","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>I am writing to local authorities affected by the recent floods to remind them of the options available where a development site with an unimplemented planning permission has flooded. Local planning authorities, in consultation with developers, are best-placed to consider whether reviewing a planning permission is appropriate, and what subsequent action may be required to ensure developments will be safe and resilient to flooding, in line with national planning policy.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:25:21.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454787/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454787/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Property Development: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will direct local planning authorities to reassess planning permissions granted to developments on floodplains that have been affected by recent flooding events.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","28182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454788","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Positive Pathway is a framework to support local authorities and their partners to design their services to prevent homelessness and meet the housing and support needs of vulnerable young people rather than a service to individual young people.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:10:48.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454788/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454788/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Housing: Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 26614, on children in care: housing, how many young people he expects to be on the Positive Pathway Framework in 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","28253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454789","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Government looked at the current pattern of all bank and public holidays as part of the Tourism strategy published in 2011, which concluded there is no overall consensus for change. There are no plans to make another consultation on this subject.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-02T17:38:27.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454789/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454789/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-24","Public Holidays","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to restart work related to his Department's pre-consultation on moving the May Bank Holiday, published in 2011.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454790","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-03","<p>In accordance with the Radiation (Emergency Preparedness and Public Information) Regulations 2001 (REPPIR) households in the area likely to be affected by a nuclear emergency, are provided with prior information to ensure they are properly informed and prepared in the unlikely event of an emergency occurring.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-03T16:02:31.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454790/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454790/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Nuclear Power: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what guidance is issued to households on dealing with a nuclear incident.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","28219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454791","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-02","<p>Plans developed under the Radiation (Emergency Preparedness and Public Information) Regulations 2001 (REPPIR) to protect the public in the unlikely event of a radiation emergency involving an operational nuclear reactor, include arrangements for the issue of stable iodine tablets. The arrangements for issuing the iodine tablets are determined at the local level and include, in some cases, the pre-distribution to households in the detailed planning area.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-02T16:14:08.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454791/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454791/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Nuclear Power: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government has issued iodine tablets to households in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","28220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454792","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-02","<p>It is Ministry of Defence policy not to provide a breakdown by geographical or economic area of the potential commercial and economic benefits of Government expenditure. By 2020 Her Majesty's Naval Base (HMNB) Clyde will become home to all the Royal Navy's submarines. This will create a single integrated submarine operating base at HMNB Clyde with 8,200 personnel employed there by 2022. This will generate substantial local economic activity.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-02T16:25:01.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454792/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454792/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Clyde Naval Base","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential (a) commercial and (b) other economic benefits of the expansion of HMNB Clyde to the surrounding towns and communities.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","28223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454793","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Braeholm facility in Helensburgh is not located in a Ministry of Defence establishment and its closure is a matter for the charity that runs the facility.</p><p>The Naval Service does recognise the support the facility has given to Service personnel and is in contact with the charity trustees to assess which of the services need to be replaced, how this will be achieved and what other future support is required, to improving the quality of life for naval personnel and their families.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-03-01T17:33:15.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454793/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454793/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Veterans: Visual Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to accommodate the Blind Veterans Association based at the Braeholm Centre in Helensburgh when that facility closes in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","28224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454794","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>In the last 12 months, the UK has been continuing Operation SHADER against Daesh in Iraq and Syria. There have been no UK military operations against Al Qaeda in the same period.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-29T16:56:45.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454794/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454794/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many military operations the UK has undertaken against (a) Daesh and (b) al-Qaeda in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","28177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454795","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-01","<p>The provision of accommodation for all naval personnel and their families is contained within the Tri-Service Accommodation Regulations which are available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/502127/20160222_-_JSP_464_Volume_1_Part_1_-_Version_3.pdf</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-03-01T17:33:42.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454795/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454795/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Clyde Naval Base: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's policy is on the provision of accommodation for naval personnel and their families visiting (a) HMNB Clyde and (b) RNAD Coulport.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","28246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454796","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>There is no intention to create a central register as described.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-29T16:52:32.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454796/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454796/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 26801, if he will create a central register of contracts and contract information for the Successor submarine programme.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","28344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454797","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>Contracts awarded to BAE Systems for the Successor programme relate to design services, long lead procurement and facilities upgrades. The total value of these contracts amounts to some £1.4 billion.</p><p>Spend to date, on these contracts, is within agreed contract limits of liability.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-29T16:53:59.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454797/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454797/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the (a) scope, (b) value and (c) cost overrun from the original value are of contracts awarded to BAE Systems for the Successor submarine programme.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","28345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454798","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>As stated in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, our latest cost estimate for manufacturing the four Successor submarine programme is £31 billion, plus a contingency of £10 billion. This includes an assessment of the likely inflation over the lifetime of the programme and the risks appropriate for a project at this stage.</p><p>I am withholding the specific estimate for inflation and risk, as to do so would prejudice the Department's commercial interests.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","28348","2016-02-29T16:56:12.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454798/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454798/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the risk provision is in the cost estimate announced in the Strategic Defence and Security Review for the Successor submarine programme.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","28346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454799","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>Optimism Bias work will be completed as part of the evidence required to inform the next investment decision.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-29T16:58:33.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454799/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454799/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he expects the formal internal scrutiny process for the current calculations for optimism bias for the Successor submarine programme to be completed.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","28347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454800","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>As stated in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, our latest cost estimate for manufacturing the four Successor submarine programme is £31 billion, plus a contingency of £10 billion. This includes an assessment of the likely inflation over the lifetime of the programme and the risks appropriate for a project at this stage.</p><p>I am withholding the specific estimate for inflation and risk, as to do so would prejudice the Department's commercial interests.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","28346","2016-02-29T16:56:12.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454800/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454800/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the provision for inflation is in the cost estimate for the Successor submarine programme.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","28348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454801","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>Information on the local authority of origin for recruits to the Regular and Reserve forces is not available.</p><p>The date at which personnel started their basic training is also not held.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence publishes UK Regular strengths by stationed location in our Quarterly Location Statistics: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/location-of-all-uk-regular-service-and-civilian-personnel-quarterly-statistics-index</p><p>Information on untrained intake into the Volunteer Reserve by stationed location in Wales is provided in the attached table.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-02-29T16:55:31.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454801/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454801/answer","20160226_PQ28420_Wales_Reserves_Table(1) PQ02517.xlsx","20160226_PQ28420_Wales_Reserves_Table(1) PQ02517.xlsx","Future Reserves 2020 volunteer Reserve.","Future Reserves 2020 volunteer Reserve.","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454801/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Armed Forces: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many recruits to the (a) Reserve and (b) armed forces in each local authority area of their origin in Wales and in each branch of service began their basic training in each of the last 12 months","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","28420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454802","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence takes the mental health of our veterans very seriously. The Department has made no representations in response to the NHS England consultation on the future of mental health support for veterans of the Armed Forces. The consultation is aimed at veterans who have used NHS veterans' mental health services, their family members and carers, and staff and organisations that are providing mental health care, treatment and support for veterans and their families.</p><p>https://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/survey/veterans-mental-health-services</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-02-29T16:53:12.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454802/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454802/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Veterans: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what representations his Department has made to the NHS England consultation on the future of mental health support for veterans of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","28314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454803","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-01","<p>Ministry of Defence spending on overseas development assistance was £3.0 million in calendar year 2013 and £2.2 million in calendar year 2014. The 2015 figure is currently undergoing assurance and is scheduled to be published on 1 April 2016. Recipients include Vanuatu, Nepal, refugees from Syria and Lebanon, nations in the Caribbean, Southern Africa and St Helena.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-03-01T17:34:12.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454803/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454803/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Ministry of Defence: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's spending was on Overseas Development Aid in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) the first 10 months of 2015-16; and what the recipient countries of that aid were.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","28267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454804","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-02","<p>Assessments are currently under way to inform decisions and refine programme costs of the individual projects at Her Majesty's Naval Base Clyde and Royal Naval Armament Depot Coulport.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-02T16:19:44.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454804/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454804/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Clyde Naval Base: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2015 to Question 11029, whether assessment of the necessary infrastructure adaptations to update the facilities at HM Naval Base Clyde and Royal Naval Armament Depot Coulport has been completed.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","28271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454805","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>The management of the Future Teaching Scholars programme is contracted to the delivery organisation, Education Development Trust. Any money spent on marketing is determined by the Education Development Trust.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T12:52:43.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454805/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454805/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on marketing for the Future Teaching Scholars programme to date.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","28315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454806","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>Regional Schools Commissioners (RSC) are supporting the development of high-performing multi-academy trusts (MAT). MATs enable academies to realise a wide range of benefits and provide the formal structure in which high-performing schools can support under-performing schools to improve.</p><p>Where there are concerns about the performance of an academy, the RSC may decide that the support of a new academy trust is needed to bring about the necessary improvements. In selecting a new trust, the RSC will evaluate its capacity, including the performance of the trust’s existing academies and its ability to provide the support required.</p><p>In order to move an underperforming academy to a new trust, the RSC may be able to use the termination powers set out in the academy’s funding agreement to require the academy to move without the agreement of the academy or the existing trust. The Education and Adoption Bill will give RSCs stronger, more consistent powers to do this with all failing and coasting academies.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-29T17:26:57.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454806/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454806/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Academies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to encourage academies to join high-performing rather than under-performing multi-academy trusts; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","28318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454807","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>Funding for the Future Teaching Scholars programme is allocated by financial year rather than by cohort. £1.3m has been allocated for financial year 2016-17. This covers the £15,000 financial incentive to Scholars, continued marketing expenditure, and all programme delivery costs.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T17:56:37.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454807/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454807/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has allocated to the Future Teaching Scholars programme for the 2016-17 cohort.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","28316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454809","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-02","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-02T11:02:45.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454809/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454809/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-24","Students: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications of a decision to leave the EU on the higher education fees status of EU students becoming classed in the same way as that for non-EU overseas students; and whether his Department plans to assess the potential effect of any such change in classification on the number of students coming from EU member states to study in the UK.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","28415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454810","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department for Education has spent the amounts shown in the table below on the following list of categories from 1 May 2015 to 31 January 2016.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>a) New IT equipment</p></td><td><p>£868,312</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>b) New furniture</p></td><td><p>£11,861</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>c) New artwork</p></td><td><p>No Expenditure</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>d) Catering and events</p></td><td><p>£326,575</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>e) Renovating buildings and facilities [1]</p></td><td><p>£9,862,679</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>f) New plants and shrubs</p></td><td><p>No Expenditure</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>g) Special Advisers’ travel expenses (including rail journeys)</p></td><td><p>£1,555</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>[1] The figure for renovating buildings and facilities is for DfE and its Agencies and does not include expenditure on school buildings.</p><p>The figures are for the Department, its Agencies and Non-Departmental Public Bodies, Government Equalities Office, Equality and Human Rights Commission and Office of the Children’s Commissioner.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T12:30:57.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454810/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454810/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Department for Education: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on (a) new IT equipment, (b) new furniture, (c) new artwork, (d) catering and events, (e) renovating its buildings and facilities, (f) new plants and shrubs and (g) special advisers' travel expenses since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454811","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department does not hold the information requested. We will be making available opportunities for voluntary and community sector organisations to bid for grants and contracts to undertake specific activity which addresses ministerial priorities, including fostering, during this Parliament.</p><p>We anticipate that grant and contract funding opportunities will be published on the Contracts Finder website, <a href="http://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a>, in due course, with further funding opportunities to be offered later in the 2016 to 2017 financial year.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-29T17:28:54.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454811/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454811/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Foster Care: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 23 February 2016 to Question 26852, what funding she expects will be provided for the Fostering Network in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","28252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454812","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>Decisions relating to teachers’ professional development rightly rest with schools, headteachers, and teachers as they are in the best position to judge their own requirements.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T12:36:19.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454812/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454812/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","English Language: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will establish a system to permit supplementary schools and mainstream schools to bid for funding to support the professional development of staff teaching English to GCSE and A-level standard; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","28260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454813","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>The exam boards are independent organisations, and the department continues to work closely with them to secure the future of all the existing language GCSEs and A levels, including Gujarati.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T12:32:27.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454813/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454813/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Gujarati Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will require the Oxford, Cambridge and RSA Examinations board to offer GCSE and A-level Gujarati examinations beyond September 2018; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","28261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454814","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>Schools can choose to teach pupils of different year groups together.</p><p>Maintained schools are required to cover the whole of the programme of study for each national curriculum subject by the time pupils reach the end of the key stage period. In planning how best to teach the curriculum, schools should consider all relevant circumstances, including the needs of their pupils, and make decisions accordingly.</p><p>The programmes of study for primary English, mathematics and science are set out on a year-by-year basis to provide a guide as to the pace that the material should be taught in these key subjects.</p><p> </p><p>The national curriculum focuses on the essential knowledge that must be taught, allowing teachers to take greater control over the wider curriculum in schools and how it is taught. Teachers are free to use their professional judgement and take account of local circumstances in deciding how best to organise their classes, including whether it would be suitable to teach mixed age pupils together. The Department has no involvement in these decisions.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:58:20.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454814/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454814/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Primary Education: Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if the new national curriculum can be taught in primary schools to mixed-age classes.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","28249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454815","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>To date we have received applications from 27 women and 23 men. We remain confident that we will secure 110 scholars by the end of summer 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T12:31:28.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454815/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454815/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applicants to the Future Teaching Scholars programme to date have been (a) women and (b) men.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","28308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454816","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Future Teaching Scholars programme is currently recruiting high achieving A level students, with the aim of securing up to 110 Scholars to start the programme in academic year 2016-17. All Scholars will be rigorously selected, including assessment of their commitment to teaching.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T12:52:18.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454816/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454816/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of (a) people who will apply for 2016-17 cohort of the Future Teaching Scholars programme, (b)applicants that will join that scheme for that year and (c) such applicants that will complete that training.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","28309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454817","Department for Education","false","2016-03-08","<p>The Department for Education has changed the approach to initial teacher training (ITT) allocations for the 2016 to 2017 academic year. The National College for Teaching and Leadership are not allocating a specific number of places to individual organisations for postgraduate ITT courses due to start in the 2016 to 2017 academic year. Instead, eligible schools, school-centred initial teacher training providers (SCITTs) and higher education institutions (HEIs) will be able to recruit as many trainees as they feel they need (subject to a limited number of controls), until the overall system has recruited a sufficient number.</p><p>As School Direct and SCITT partnerships cover large geographical areas, we are monitoring recruitment at a regional level only. To date, the only challenge in geographical distribution of ITT places has been found in the London region in recruitment to primary, which was recruiting slower than other regions. In this case we have allowed school led routes (i.e. School Direct (tuition fee) and SCITTs) in this region to continue to recruit to primary courses to ensure that enough trainees are recruited.</p><p>We are prepared to use reserve recruitment controls in other subjects, or for other regions as required.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-08T12:33:31.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454817/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454817/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that the supply of newly-qualified teachers is not affected by imbalances in the distribution of teacher training places at a sub-regional level.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454818","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>There will be places available for all Scholars after they successfully complete their undergraduate degree and commence their initial teacher training from the 2019-20 academic year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:57:51.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454818/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454818/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many spaces have been set aside on initial teacher training courses for the 2016-17 cohort of the future teaching scholars programme.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","28174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454819","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>For the 2014/15 and 2015/16 academic years, we operated an allocations system to distribute initial teacher training (ITT) places directly to School Direct lead schools, school-centred initial teacher training providers (SCITTs) and higher education institutions (HEIs). For recent years detailed initial and final allocations data for individual HEIs can be found on GOV.UK:</p><ul><li><p>2015/16 GOV.UK links:</p><ul><li><p>Initial allocations: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-allocations-for-academic-year-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-allocations-for-academic-year-2015-to-2016</a></p></li><li><p>Final allocations summary: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-itt-recruitment-controls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-itt-recruitment-controls</a></p></li><li><p>Summary of final core postgraduate ITT places available to all HEIs in:</p><ul><li><p>(a) history = 243;</p></li><li><p>(b) geography = 462;</p></li><li><p>(c) English = 866; and</p></li><li><p>(d) STEM* = 5081)</p></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>2014/15 GOV.UK links:</p><ul><li><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-allocations-for-academic-year-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-allocations-for-academic-year-2014-to-2015</a></p></li><li><p>Summary of final core postgraduate places available to all HEIs in:</p><ul><li><p>(a) history = 363;</p></li><li><p>(b) geography = 472;</p></li><li><p>(c) English = 867 and</p></li><li><p>(d) STEM* = 5086)</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p>*STEM subjects include: Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Mathematics, Design &amp; Technology and Computing.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:56:42.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454819/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454819/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which higher education institution providers of initial teacher education have reduced their allocation for PGCE secondary training in (a) history, (b) geography, (c) English and (d) STEM subjects in 2015-16; and what that reduction is as a proportion of that provider's 2014-15 allocations in each case.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454820","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>Special advisers have not accompanied any Ministers on an international visit since 1 October 2015.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:57:29.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454820/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454820/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Department for Education: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, on how many occasions a special adviser of her Department has accompanied a Minister on a foreign trip since 1 October 2015; and what the cost of that travel has been.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454821","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Department for Education uses the Teacher Supply Model (TSM) to estimate the national requirements for the number of postgraduate Initial Teacher Training places to meet demand, including mathematics.</p><p>The 2016/17 version of the TSM, which was used to inform the 2016/17 ITT recruitment process, along with a user guide explaining the methodology in detail, is available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:54:01.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454821/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454821/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make an assessment of the adequacy of the supply of newly-qualified mathematics teachers in Stoke-on-Trent.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454822","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>I am not aware of any discussions that have taken place with representatives from the National Baccalaureate Trust.</p><p>The Department recently consulted on the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) asking for views on how schools will manage the challenges associated with implementing the commitment that the EBacc becomes the default position for all mainstream secondary pupils. The consultation closed on 29 January and we received 2,755 responses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:57:04.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454822/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454822/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","National Baccalaureate Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions (a) Ministers, (b) special advisers and (c) senior officials of her Department have had with representatives from the National Baccalaureate Trust since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454823","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Department for Education has changed the approach to initial teacher training (ITT) allocations for the 2016 to 2017 academic year. The National College for Teaching and Leadership are not allocating a specific number of places to individual organisations for postgraduate ITT courses due to start in the 2016 to 2017 academic year. Instead, eligible schools, school-centred initial teacher training providers (SCITTs) and higher education institutions (HEIs) will be able to recruit as many trainees as they feel they need (subject to a limited number of controls), until the overall system has recruited a sufficient number.</p><p> </p><p>School Direct lead schools, SCITTs and universities across all regions have been given greater freedom for the 2016/17 academic year to manage their recruitment according to local need.</p><p> </p><p>We are monitoring regional recruitment across all subjects, including the West Midlands region. However, as School Direct and SCITT partnerships cover large geographical areas, we are not monitoring recruitment at a sub-regional level.</p><p>To date, the only challenge in geographical distribution of ITT places has been found in the London region in recruitment to primary, which was recruiting slower than other regions. In this case we have allowed school led routes (i.e. School Direct (tuition fee) and SCITTs) in this region to continue to recruit to primary courses to ensure that enough trainees are recruited. For all other regions, recruitment is broadly the same as in 2015/16 with some areas showing an increase.</p><p> </p><p>We are prepared to use reserve recruitment controls in other subjects, or for other regions, as required.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-22T10:47:19.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454823/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454823/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make an assessment of the adequacy of the distribution of teacher training places in the (a) North Staffordshire sub-region and (b) West Midlands region.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454824","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>Where local authorities dispose of or change the use of buildings or other assets funded wholly or partly through Sure Start capital grants, they must repay the money through the claw-back process.</p><p>The Department for Education has a thorough set of monitoring arrangements in place regarding claw-back rules. Local authorities are required to notify the department of each and every proposed change of services and provide details about the level of early years services that are to continue. The department then considers if the local authority has continued to offer a sufficient level of early years services for children and their families from the building in question to meet the original aims of the grant.</p><p>If the department is satisfied that the funding for the asset will continue to be used for purposes consistent with the grant, the department may defer claw-back. Deferring claw-back means that we accept the change of usage at that time, however, the department retains its interest in the asset and if in the future the asset has its usage changed, is transferred or otherwise disposed of, and does not continue to meet the purposes of the grant the local authority must inform the department and we will claw-back the funding. The department’s interest in an asset funded by Sure Start capital grants is 25 years from designation of the building. If the grant was used to purchase capital items or re-furbish an existing asset, the length of time and value of any claw-back depends on the depreciation value of the items, according to local authority depreciation rules.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","28207","2016-02-29T17:24:37.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454824/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454824/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and which local authorities have notified her Department about plans to dispose of grant-funded assets through the (a) sale, (b) transfer and (c) change of use of children's centres under the requirements of the Sure Start Early Years and Childcare Grant.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28205"
