"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454826","Department for Education","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Future Teaching Scholars programme received 50 applications in the first recruitment round. We remain confident that we will secure 110 scholars by the end of summer 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-29T12:32:01.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454826/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454826/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications her Department received to the first application round for the Future Teaching Scholars programme.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","28217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454827","Department for Energy and Climate Change","true","2016-03-03","<p>The Sellafield Change Programme is being put into place to improve business performance and provide greater value for the public purse while maintaining the priority of safe and secure operations. In relation to terms and conditions of employment, there are two improvements being proposed by Sellafield Ltd: first, changes to the pay and grading structure of existing staff, to ensure that pay and grading is fair and equitable; and second, new terms for new starters that are more closely aligned to market practice. In both cases the business has and will continue to engage with its employees and their representatives on the proposed changes.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the change programme are available<ins class="ministerial"> in the attached.</ins> <del class="ministerial">at:</del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial"><a href="http://www.nda.gov.uk/contracts-and-competition/sellafield-model-change-programme" target="_blank">http://www.nda.gov.uk/contracts-and-competition/sellafield-model-change-programme</a>.</del></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-03T15:55:17.073Z","2016-03-08T13:52:35.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454827/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454827/answer","New_Management_Arrangements_for_Sellafield_-_Stakeholder_Briefing.pdf","New_Management_Arrangements_for_Sellafield_-_Stakeholder_Briefing.pdf","New Management Arrangements: Sellafield","New Management Arrangements: Sellafield","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454827/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454827/answer/previousversion/48819","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Sellafield: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what changes have been proposed to the existing terms and conditions of the Sellafield workforce under the workforce reform initiative.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","28221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454828","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-03","<p>I have made no such assessment. Any new coal plant must demonstrate carbon capture and storage on at least 300 MW of its proposed generating capacity and comply with the Emissions Performance Standard.</p><p> </p><p>Coal fired power stations without abatement are not consistent with meeting our decarbonisation objectives. This is why the Government has committed to consulting on phasing out unabated coal by 2025 and to restricting the amount of coal generation in 2023.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-03T15:49:20.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454828/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454828/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of supporting the deployment of ultra-super critical coal fired power stations similar to those planned by China and Germany; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","28242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454829","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-29","<p>The number of jobs imported coal supports in each of its source countries is not information that the Department of Energy and Climate Change holds.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-29T14:53:43.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454829/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454829/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Coal: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will place in the Library any information her Department holds on the number of jobs imported coal supports in each of its source countries; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","28243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454830","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-01","<p>With the exception of proposals for nuclear generating stations, the choice of location for any energy generation project is a matter for the developer concerned, and the location`s suitability will be considered as part of the consent application process. Any new coal plant must demonstrate carbon capture and storage on at least 300 MW of its proposed generating capacity and comply with the Emissions Performance Standard.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-01T13:11:46.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454830/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454830/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Coal Fired Power Stations: Blyth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will assess the suitability of the hinterland of the Port of Blyth as a location for an ultra-super critical coal fired power station; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","28244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454831","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Sellafield Change Programme is being put into place to improve business performance and provide greater value for the public purse while maintaining the priority of safe and secure operations. Sellafield Ltd will continue to offer quality employment for many people for many years and is looking at how it can deliver the decommissioning mission as effectively and efficiently as possible and in a way that strengthens the local economy. Sellafield Ltd is engaging the workforce and its representatives on plans to improve the business and specifically on what this will mean for employees.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the change programme are available at <a href="http://www.nda.gov.uk/contracts-and-competition/sellafield-model-change-programme" target="_blank">http://www.nda.gov.uk/contracts-and-competition/sellafield-model-change-programme</a>.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-01T13:10:13.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454831/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454831/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Sellafield: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the Sellafield Workforce Reform programme on the Sellafield workforce.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","28222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454832","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government expects network companies to use the most appropriate technologies available to provide the required connection for the particular project in line with its customer’s connection needs, its statutory obligations to have regard to the environment and to mitigating adverse impacts where reasonable, and relevant planning requirements.</p><p> </p><p>This is reinforced by the Government’s energy National Policy Statements (NPSs) in particular NPS EN-1[1] and NPS EN-5<strong>2</strong>, which make it clear that proper consideration should be given to all feasible means of connection, including undergrounding.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/47854/1938-overarching-nps-for-energy-en1.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/47854/1938-overarching-nps-for-energy-en1.pdf</a></em></p><p><strong><em>[2]</em></strong><em> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/47858/1942-national-policy-statement-electricity-networks.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/47858/1942-national-policy-statement-electricity-networks.pdf</a></em></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-29T14:54:14.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454832/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454832/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Electric Cables","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps the Government has taken to encourage underground cabling connecting (a) wind farm and (b) other such installations to distribution centres in order to present visual amenity and prevent adverse environmental impacts.","false","Biography information for Dr James Davies","Vale of Clwyd","Dr James Davies","28416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454833","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Department is currently working with industry to establish the Microgeneration Certification Scheme (MCS) as a legal entity. The accessibility of MCS standards referenced in the RHI regulations will be considered as part of that process to ensure that those standards which are mandatory for the purpose of the RHI remain publicly available.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-01T09:07:21.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454833/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454833/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will ensure that all standards explicitly linked to the Renewable Heat Incentive are non-commercialised and publicly available to all relevant parties who may wish to offer services related to the implementation of that initiative.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","28417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454834","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Department is in the process of working with the microgeneration industry to establish the Microgeneration Certification Scheme (MCS) as a legal entity that will operate independently of the Government. There is an established process for alternative schemes to MCS to come forward through the United Kingdom Accreditation Service and equivalent accreditation bodies in the EU. For example, through this process the Solar Keymark product scheme for solar thermal products has been recognised and treated as equivalent to MCS. In addition, the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) regulations give Ofgem the power to determine scheme equivalency; and they are currently finalising this process for equivalent schemes to be considered in specific reference to the RHI.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-01T09:12:45.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454834/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454834/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Microgeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department is assessing potential alternatives to the Microgeneration Certification Scheme to which the Renewable Heat Incentive is linked.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","28418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454835","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-02","<p>Data on Defra’s Official Development Assistance funding is publicly available on the GOV.UK website where the Department for International Development’s document entitled “Dataset underlying SID 2015” is available for download at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistics-on-international-development-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistics-on-international-development-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>The dataset provides a breakdown of spending by calendar year, recipient country and channel of delivery (in line with the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s Development Assistance Committee guidance). Defra-related information within the dataset can be found as follows:</p><p> </p><p>(i) Darwin Initiative projects –for 2013 funding see rows 27384 – 27496 and 32391 – 32450; for 2014 funding see rows 32458 – 32864, 34206 to 34416, 35856 to 36904, 37230 to 37234 and 40575 to 40628.</p><p>(ii) International Climate Fund projects – for 2013 funding see rows 27448 and 27449; for 2014 funding see row 33528.</p><p>(iii) Illegal Wildlife Trade - for 2014 funding see rows 33200, 33201, 33879, 33880 and 34845.</p><p> </p><p>Information on 2015 spending will be available when the next updated dataset is published later in the year.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-03-02T10:28:54.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454835/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454835/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-24","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her Department's spending was on Overseas Development Aid in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) the first 10 months of 2015-16; and what the recipient countries of that aid were.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","28264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454836","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-29","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave on the 22 February 2016, PQ UIN 26438. The obligation to transpose and implement EU environmental law applies across the whole of the UK, although the responsibility for transposition and implementation in this area is a competence of the devolved administrations.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-29T17:42:56.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454836/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454836/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-24","EU Environmental Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 264385, what steps her Department has taken to ensure that EU environmental law is transposed and implemented across the whole of the UK.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","28237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454837","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-29","<p>We have no plans to make such an assessment.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-29T14:26:32.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454837/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454837/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-24","Animal Products: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department plans to make an assessment of the environmental effects of the disposal of imported (a) animal blood, faeces and urine and (b) other biological by-products in rural areas of the UK.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","28245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454838","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-29","<p>We do not intend to measure household food insecurity because there is no single definition of food insecurity. The Food Insecurity Experience Scale (FIES) is one method, but the factors that impact on household food security are complex. There are multiple indicators such as quality, variety and desirability of diet as well as total intake, not all of which are measured consistently. It is therefore very difficult and potentially misleading to develop a single classification of food insecurity.</p><p> </p><p>The OECD ‘Society at a Glance 2014’ report published figures showing that the proportion of those who say they are finding it difficult to afford food in the UK declined over the past 5 years 2007 - 2012: from 9.8% to 8.1%. This was based on Gallup World Poll data which actually used one of the questions which form part of the FIES.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-29T17:11:42.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454838/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454838/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-24","Malnutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will include the Food Insecurity Experience Scale survey in the next Family Food survey in order to assess households' vulnerability to hunger.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","28227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454839","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government (Defra, the Department for Transport, Food Standards Agency and the Home Office) accepted 137 of more than 200 recommendations made by the Farming Regulation Task Force in 2011.</p><p>The Farming Regulation Task Force Implementation Group published a final assessment of our delivery in April 2014 in which they concluded that we had completed or made progress against the vast majority of the accepted recommendations. The remaining 27 recommendations are currently being reviewed as part of the ‘Cutting Red Tape: Review of the Information managements in the Agricultural Sector’. A report on the findings of this review will be published shortly.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-29T16:44:07.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454839/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454839/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-24","Agriculture: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to implement the findings of the Report of the Independent Farming Regulation Taskforce, published in May 2011.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","28213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454840","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-01","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>No applications have been received in 2016 for the emergency authorisation of neonicotinoids.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-01T15:23:59.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454840/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454840/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-24","Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many applications for emergency authorisation for the use of neonicotinoids have been received in 2016; and how many of those applications have been granted.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","28298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454841","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) has had no discussions with the Hungarian government on this issue.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-02T15:46:21.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454841/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454841/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","Hungary: Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Hungarian government on the sale of residency bonds through off-shore companies.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454842","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my previous answers of 14 December 2015 (PQ 18601) and 17 December 2015 (PQ 19436). The information requested in the years prior to 2011 is not held centrally and can be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-02T15:46:01.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454842/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454842/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","Romania: Mass Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the government of Romania about the activities of (a) Central Media Enterprise, (b) Adrian Sârbu and (c) Ronald Lauder in (i) 1995 to 1999, (ii) 2000 to 2010 and (iii) 2011 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","28332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454843","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Decision of the Heads of State or Government, meeting within the European Council, concerning a new settlement for the United Kingdom within the European Union, will be published in the Department’s Treaty Series.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-01T17:42:29.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454843/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454843/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454843/answer/previousversion/47993","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","European Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Decision of the Heads of State or Government, meeting within the European Council, on 18 and 19 February 2016 will be added to his Department's Treaty Series 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","28381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454844","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), has had no discussions with the UN Secretary General on the supply of arms and other military equipment sales to Saudi Arabia.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-03-02T15:35:00.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454844/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454844/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the UN Secretary General on the supply of arms and other military equipment sales to Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","28413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454845","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The central element of the agreement is an International Law Decision agreed by the Heads of State or Government of the Member States of the EU and is a binding international treaty. The European Commission has committed to bring forward new legislation where it is needed to implement the UK’s new settlement. These European Commission proposals will be subject to the normal legislative procedures set out in the Treaties. The President and representatives of the major political groups in the European Parliament were consulted on the UK’s new settlement and both Ministers and officials plan furhter contact with MEPs.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-03T16:47:17.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454845/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454845/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the agreement reached at the February European Council is not amended by the European Parliament after the date of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","28178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454846","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Official Development Assistance spending was:</p><p>in financial year (FT) 2013-14 - £321 million;<br>in FT 2014-15 - £344 million;<br>and in the first 10 months of FY 2015-16 - £260 million</p><p>We have provided ODA funds to all countries on the OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) list except for Central African Republic, Djibouti, Sao Tome and Principe, Micronesia, Tokelau, Gabon, Niue, Palau, Wallis and Futuna. The DAC list can be found here: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/stats/documentupload/DAC%20List%20of%20ODA%20Recipients%202014%20final.pdf." target="_blank">http://www.oecd.org/dac/stats/documentupload/DAC%20List%20of%20ODA%20Recipients%202014%20final.pdf.</a></p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-02T16:17:13.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454846/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454846/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's spending was on Overseas Development Aid in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) the first 10 months of 2015-16; and what the recipient countries of that aid were.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","28265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454847","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Decision of the Heads of State or Government, meeting within the European Council, concerning a new settlement for the United Kingdom within the European Union, is legally binding. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), has been clear that this deal protects the UK’s rights as a country outside the Eurozone, and from any future integration.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-01T17:41:59.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454847/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454847/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454847/answer/previousversion/47997","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","Economic and Monetary Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the commitments by the UK not to create obstacles to, but facilitate such deepening of the Eurozone, to sincere cooperation with the Eurozone, not to impede the implementation of legal acts directly linked to the functioning of the euro area to refrain from measures which could jeopardise the attainment of the objectives of economic and monetary union contained in the Decision of the Heads of State or Government, meeting within the European Council, on 18 and 19 February 2016 are legally binding; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","28383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454848","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The decision of the Heads of State or Government, meeting within the European Council, concerning a new settlement for the United Kingdom within the European Union, is legally binding. The Government is confident that all the commitments in the Decision will be implemented by the Member States and EU Institutions.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-02T15:40:26.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454848/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454848/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454848/answer/previousversion/47998","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-24","European Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, in which court the commitment in point 7 of Section A of the Decision of the Heads of State or Government, meeting within the European Council on 18 and 19 February 2016, to incorporate the substance of the section into the EU Treaties is enforceable.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","28385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454849","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-29T16:00:35.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454849/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454849/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Mental Health Services: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on how many occasions mental health trusts in London have paid for private beds since 2010; and on each such occasion (a) from which organisation the bed was purchased and (b) what the cost of that purchase was to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","28424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454850","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Policing and Crime Bill, currently before Parliament, will seek to reduce the maximum length of time a person can be detained under section 135 or 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983 from 72 to 24 hours, to make clear that people should be assessed as quickly as possible.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-29T09:40:47.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454850/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454850/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Mental Health Services: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on how many occasions a Mental Health Act 1983 assessment requested on someone in custody in London took longer than 24 hours in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","28425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454851","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The provision and commissioning of police custody nurses is the responsibility of individual Police and Crime Commissioners, and police custody nurse staffing and availability levels are an operational policing matter in conjunction with the custody healthcare service provider. Information on these issues is not held centrally by the Home Office.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","28375","2016-03-01T16:07:11.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454851/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454851/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Police Stations: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police stations in London (a) had and (b) did not have custody nurses working in them in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","28426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454852","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>We are committed to achieving parity of esteem between mental health and physical health. The Mental Health Taskforce estimates that the priority recommendations for the National Health Service set out in their report will cost an additional £1 billion annually by the year 2020/21. By the end of this Parliament we will make the Taskforce’s recommendations a reality.</p><p> </p><p>This builds on the £1.4 billion over this Parliament that has been previously announced for transforming children and young people’s mental health and improving support for eating disorders.</p><p> </p><p>All of the Taskforce report recommendations are funded from within the overall envelope agreed in the Spending Review. All of the £1 billion announced with the Taskforce report represents additional investment over and above what was allocated to the NHS in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>We are already spending more money on mental health than ever before – an estimated £11.7 billion last year. This shows our commitment to achieving an equal status between mental and physical health services. We have been clear that commissioners must continue to increase investment in mental health services each year at a level which at least matches their overall expenditure increase.</p><p><br> We will monitor this closely to ensure this happens and know that clinical commissioning group spend is on track to increase as expected.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-29T17:20:01.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454852/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454852/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Mental Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 3 on page 5 of the Five Year Forward View Mental Health Task Force report, published on 15 February 2016, if he will make it his policy to provide equal funding for mental health services.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","28310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454853","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>No such assessment has been made. However, the Right Care programme actively uses variation between clinical commissioning groups to help identify those diseases or conditions that have the potential for greatest improvement. Indicators used include prevalence, treatment and outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Atlas of Variation, Commissioning for Value Packs and indicators in the National Health Service Outcomes Framework and Public Health Outcomes Framework provide publicly accessible resources to compare geographical areas and highlight health inequalities and other variation across a wide variety of indicators.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-29T14:18:20.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454853/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454853/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of in which type of healthcare there is greatest geographical disparity of treatment (a) availability, (b) choice and (c) outcomes across England.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","28312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454854","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>Data on the number and proportion of children aged 5–16 years diagnosed with a conduct disorder is not routinely collected centrally. The most recent survey, <em>Mental health of children and young people in Great Britain, 2004, </em>published by the Office for National Statistics in 2005, showed that 5.8% of children aged five to 16 had conduct disorders. This represents 60.4% of the 9.6% of children with any mental health disorder at that time.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Department is commissioning a new national prevalence survey of children and young people’s mental health – the first since 2004. The survey will estimate the extent of mental ill health in the 2-19 year old population. Final publication of findings is expected in 2018.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-29T09:52:08.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454854/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454854/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Behaviour Disorders: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of (a) all children and (b) children with mental health conditions aged five to 16 have conduct disorder.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","28311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454855","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>Information on the number of people using National Health Service funded adult secondary mental health services, including those who spent time on the Care Programme Approach (CPA), is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total People</p></td><td><p>1,287,730</p></td><td><p>1,607,153</p></td><td><p>1,590,332</p></td><td><p>1,746,698</p></td><td><p>1,835,996</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>People on CPA</p></td><td><p>263,935</p></td><td><p>407,370</p></td><td><p>359,368</p></td><td><p>357,732</p></td><td><p>335,727</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures includes people who have been on CPA for a number of months or years as well as people who had only recently been assigned to CPA. These figures count each individual once, regardless of the number of times they accessed services in the year.</p><p> </p><p>Because of major changes to the Mental Health Minimum Dataset and submission process, figures for these years are not directly comparable. The scope was expanded to include independent sector providers in 2011/12 and learning disability services in 2014/15. Major changes to the submission process between 2010/11 and 2011/12 also contributed to an overall increase in numbers.</p><p> </p><p>A snapshot count of people on CPA at the end of 2014/15 who had been on CPA for at least 12 months and the number and proportion of these who had received a CPA review within the last 12 months is shown in the following table. It has not been possible to provide data for earlier years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>March 2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>People on CPA at the end of the month who had been on CPA for 12 months</p></td><td><p>126,679</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>People on CPA for 12 months with a review in the previous 12 months</p></td><td><p>101,592</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage of people on CPA for 12 months with a review</p></td><td><p>80.2%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The process of the CPA recognises that reviews should be held at least every year. However, where an individual’s needs are sufficiently complicated to require more complex care co-ordination, the frequency of review meetings will be increased.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-29T17:54:07.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454855/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454855/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people with severe and long-term mental health issues and whose care is coordinated through the Care Programme Approach in each year since 2010 had had a formal meeting to review their care in the previous 12 months.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","28313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454856","Department of Health","false","2016-03-03","<p>In 2013-14 the Department spent £11.66 million on Official Development Assistance. In 2014-15 the Department spent £11.5 million on Official Development Assistance.</p><p>The Department’s Official Development Assistance in 2013-14 and 2014-15 is a proportion of the Department’s assessed contribution or subscription, to the World Health Organization (WHO). The subscription funds our contribution to all the functions of the WHO. The WHO provides the leadership and co-ordination role in global health for all its 194 member countries. As part of this role it provides technical support and assistance on the ground.</p><p>WHO is able to use the assessed contribution flexibly to fund its priorities as agreed by the United Kingdom and other member countries. We do not therefore have specific data of individual countries supported through our assessed contribution. However, more specific information on WHO funding flows to regions, individual countries and programmes can be found on WHO’s web portal at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://extranet.who.int/programmebudget/Biennium2014/Financing#_blank" target="_blank">http://extranet.who.int/programmebudget/Biennium2014/Financing</a></p><p> </p><p>The 2015 Official Development Assistance figures have not yet been finalised. The Department for International Development will release the 2015 figures in the National Statistics publication on 1 April 2016.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-03T17:41:32.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454856/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454856/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Department of Health: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's spending was on Overseas Development Aid in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) the first 10 months of 2015-16; and what the recipient countries of that aid were.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","28266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454857","Department of Health","false","2016-03-02","<p>We congratulate the British Heart Foundation (BHF) on its Wear It Beat It campaign, which aims to raise funds for research into heart disease.</p><p> </p><p>Heart disease is a vital area of research. The Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) funds a wide range of research relating to these conditions, spending £49 million on cardiovascular disease research in 2014/15. The NIHR works in partnership with the BHF and other medical research charities.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-02T18:15:50.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454857/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454857/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Heart Diseases: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he has taken to support the British Heart Foundations' Wear It Beat It campaign.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","28365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454858","Department of Health","false","2016-03-03","<p>A search of the Department’s central correspondence system shows that the Department received 22 representations that made direct or indirect reference to the report `Surrogacy in the UK: Myth Busting and Reform' since it was published in November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has no current plans to change the legislation in respect of surrogacy arrangements.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","28367 ; 28369","2016-03-03T16:31:43.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454858/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454858/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Surrogate Motherhood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received on the proposals contained in the report, Surrogacy in the UK: Myth Busting and Reform, published in November 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","28366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454859","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>Dental activity is measured through the number of courses of treatment delivered. Data has been provided for the number of courses of treatment for 0 to 17 year olds for the period 1 April 2014 to 31 March 2015. Final data for 2015/16 will be published in August 2016.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Geography</p></td><td><p>Courses of treatment (CoT) for child patients</p></td><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nottingham North Constituency</p></td><td><p>21,806</p></td><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nottingham Local Authority</p></td><td><p>67,023</p></td><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England and Wales</p></td><td><p>11,509,227</p></td><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Sources: </em></p><p>NHS Dental Services of the NHS Business Services Authority</p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><ol><li>A CoT is defined as:</li></ol><p>a. an examination of a patient, an assessment of their oral health, and the planning of any treatment to be provided to that patient as a result of that examination and assessment; and</p><p>b. the provision of any planned treatment (including any treatment planned at a time other than the time of the initial examination) to that patient.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-29T10:36:31.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454859/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454859/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many 0 to 17 year olds have received dental treatment in (a) Nottingham North constituency, (b) Nottingham and (c) the UK in 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","28185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454860","Department of Health","false","2016-03-02","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has produced guidance to support local authorities in their responsibility to improve dental health and reduce inequalities among children in their area. PHE has also developed guidance for dental teams on preventing dental disease in their patients. Advice has recently been published by the National Institute of Health and Care Excellence.</p><p>The Department will be launching the Childhood Obesity Strategy in the summer. It will look at everything that contributes to a child becoming overweight and obese, including sugar which is a cause of tooth decay.</p><p>Overall, children’s access to National Health Service dentistry remains consistently high, with the number of children seen in the 24 months to December 2015 by an NHS dentist standing at 8.1 million or 69.5% of the population. 104,000 more children saw an NHS dentist in England in the 24 month period ending 31 December 2015, compared with the same period ending 31 December 2014.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-02T18:13:09.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454860/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454860/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the proportion of five-year olds eligible for free school meals with severe or extensive tooth decay.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","28186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454861","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department is leading work to develop an indicator of child development at age 2-2½ to be included in the Public Health Outcomes Framework (PHOF) from 2017. The population measure will give a national picture of child development at age 2 and will also help local areas to assess the impact of services for 0-2 year olds and inform local commissioning.</p><p> </p><p>Since April 2015, the Department has asked all health visiting teams in England to use the evidence based Ages and Stages Questionnaires (ASQ-3) as part of children’s health and development reviews at age 2-2½ to generate data for the indicator. The Department has worked with Health Education England to develop e-learning materials to support health professionals using ASQ-3 as part of the two year review.</p><p> </p><p>From October 2015, health visiting providers were asked to report ASQ-3 scores to the Children and Young People’s Health Services dataset, which is being developed by the Health and Social Care Information Centre. The dataset is expected to publish its first report in April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England will draw on ASQ-3 data from the children’s dataset to report the PHOF outcome measure of child development at age 2-2½, reporting on a yearly basis the percentage of children with a positive outcome across all five domains of development in ASQ-3 at age 2-2½. The first reporting of the outcome measure is planned for inclusion in the PHOF in spring 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-29T14:02:11.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454861/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454861/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Health: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress his Department has made on developing a national measure of child development at age two to two-and-a-half as part of the public health framework; and when he expects that measure to be introduced.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454862","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has not yet published its final updated guidance on the use of immunosuppressive therapy for kidney transplant in adults (review of TA85) or on the use of immunosuppressive therapy for kidney transplant in children and young people (review of TA99). NICE is developing resource impact reports to support implementation of its guidance which will be published alongside its final technology appraisal guidance.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","28239 ; 28356","2016-02-29T14:15:22.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454862/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454862/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Transplant Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimates he has made of the additional resources needed and the cost of providing additional dialysis capacity for those patients who will no longer be suitable for a kidney transplant and for those patients whose transplant graft fails due as a result of restrictions in the range of immunosuppressant agents that will be introduced if the recommendations of the NICE review of TA 85 [ID456] are upheld at appeal.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sheryll Murray","South East Cornwall","Mrs Sheryll Murray","28211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454863","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>National immunisation programmes are introduced on the advice of the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), the independent expert body that advises the Government on all immunisation matters. JCVI’s recommendations are based on a comprehensive and careful review of a wide range of evidence including information from medical experts.</p><p> </p><p>JCVI reviewed the available evidence on meningitis B vaccine and recommended a national Meningococcal B (MenB) immunisation programme for infants. The MenB vaccine is first offered to babies at 2 months of age, with further doses offered when they reach 4 and 12 months of age.</p><p> </p><p>MenB was introduced into the NHS programme in September 2015. JCVI keeps the eligibility criteria of all vaccination programmes under review and considers new evidence as it becomes available. If JCVI provides further advice about the programme, we will consider this.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","28232","2016-02-29T18:21:57.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454863/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454863/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Meningitis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to urgently consult with medical authorities on ensuring a meningitis B vaccine is provided to all young children; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","28230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454864","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has not yet published its final updated guidance on the use of immunosuppressive therapy for kidney transplant in adults (review of TA85) or on the use of immunosuppressive therapy for kidney transplant in children and young people (review of TA99). NICE is developing resource impact reports to support implementation of its guidance which will be published alongside its final technology appraisal guidance.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","28211 ; 28356","2016-02-29T14:15:22.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454864/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454864/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Kidney Diseases: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on (a) resourcing of kidney and dialysis care in Plymouth Hospitals and Royal Cornwall Hospitals NHS Trusts and (b) care for kidney patients from South East Cornwall of the recent NICE ruling on provision of immune-suppressant drugs.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sheryll Murray","South East Cornwall","Mrs Sheryll Murray","28239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454865","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>We are planning to go out to consultation shortly.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-29T15:39:10.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454865/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454865/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 26546, when he expects to publish the consultation document on introducing fixed recoverable costs in clinical negligence claims.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","28240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454866","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>National immunisation programmes are introduced on the advice of the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), the independent expert body that advises the Government on all immunisation matters. JCVI’s recommendations are based on a comprehensive and careful review of a wide range of evidence including information from medical experts.</p><p> </p><p>JCVI reviewed the available evidence on meningitis B vaccine and recommended a national Meningococcal B (MenB) immunisation programme for infants. The MenB vaccine is first offered to babies at 2 months of age, with further doses offered when they reach 4 and 12 months of age.</p><p> </p><p>MenB was introduced into the NHS programme in September 2015. JCVI keeps the eligibility criteria of all vaccination programmes under review and considers new evidence as it becomes available. If JCVI provides further advice about the programme, we will consider this.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","28230","2016-02-29T18:21:57.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454866/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454866/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Meningitis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department last consulted medical authorities on the potential merits of making the meningitis B vaccine available on the NHS for all children; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","28232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454867","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>Meningococcal B (MenB) disease is a devastating disease which can have tragic consequences. We understand that in March 2014 Mr and Mrs Timmins met consultants at Walsall Healthcare NHS Trust to discuss their son’s care following his tragic death in December 2013.</p><p> </p><p>In September 2015, we became the first country in the world to offer a national and publicly funded MenB immunisation programme using the Bexsero vaccine to protect infants. The programme follows the advice of the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation, the independent, expert body which advises Government on all immunisation matters. Infants are vaccinated at two months of age, with further doses offered when they reach four and 12 months of age, thereby protecting groups with the highest risk.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-29T18:19:05.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454867/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454867/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Meningitis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to meet Mr and Mrs Timmins to discuss the death in 2013  of their son from meningitis B and the future provision of a vaccine for that disease on the NHS; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","28231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454868","Department of Health","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department estimates that it would pay out £570 million over the next 45 years, based on the existing unreformed scheme. The Department currently anticipates that it will disburse the same sum under a reformed scheme plus the additional £125 million over the current spending review period of five years. We are currently consulting on the reformed scheme and are unable to estimate the future average annual spend beyond the current spending review or the categories of spend for the period. For the current spending review period the planned expenditure is £47.5 million for each of the next five years.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-29T14:00:06.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454868/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454868/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of the £570 million referred to in paragraph 0.5 of his Department's paper, Infected blood: reform of financial and other support, published in January 2016, will be spent in each year of the programme; what the average spend per recipient will be in each such year; and in what categories of spending that funding will fall in each such year.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","28374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454869","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The provision and commissioning of police custody nurses is the responsibility of individual Police and Crime Commissioners, and police custody nurse staffing and availability levels are an operational policing matter in conjunction with the custody healthcare service provider. Information on these issues is not held centrally by the Home Office.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","28426","2016-03-01T16:07:11.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454869/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454869/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Police Stations: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions custody nurses were not available in police stations when required in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","28375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454870","Department of Health","false","2016-03-03","<p>Regarding the £8.4 billion real terms increase in funding, NHS England (NHSE) does not stipulate a specific spend level for commissioning bodies, this is to be determined by national policy directives like parity of esteem and specific local needs based assessment. At a commissioning stream level, NHSE has set a principal commitment to achieving mental health parity of esteem. Through its assurance process NHSE will hold individual commissioners to account for increasing spend on mental health in line with their increase in allocations, taking account of the additional mental health funding that has been received. <br> <br> The difference between the 2015/16 funding for children’s and young people’s mental health in NHSE baseline and subsequent increase in funding over the five-year period from 2016-17 to 2020-21 is included in the £8.4 billion growth in the Mandate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department allocates funding to NHS England as set out in the government’s mandate to NHSE and accompanying financial directions. The mandate to NHSE for 2016-17 and accompanying directions are both available at:</p><p><br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/nhs-mandate-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/nhs-mandate-2016-to-2017</a></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-03T18:03:21.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454870/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454870/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Mental Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 2 of Delivering the Forward View: NHS Planning Guidance, published in December 2015, how much of the £8.4 billion real terms increase in NHS funding by 2020-21 is allocated to mental health; whether that figure includes funding for children and young people's mental health announced before the 2015 General Election; and under which of his Department's budget headings that funding has been allocated.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","28336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454871","Department of Health","false","2016-03-02","<p>Following a review of the National Clinical Directors (NCDs), NHS England will be supported by 16 NCDs from 1 April 2016. Objectives for the NCDs will be set according to the priority areas and major programmes, as set out in the Mandate and planning guidance, and where there are established programmes of service improvement.</p><p> </p><p>Where there will no longer be a specific NCD role for renal disease, NHS England will secure expert clinical advice from its Clinical Networks and through its relationships with professional bodies and by appointing clinical advisors.</p><p> </p><p>Think Kidneys is scheduled to continue until the end of 2016, and a strategy for the longer term is being developed. Wider work on renal disease will be taken forward through the specialised commissioning infrastructure within NHS England and through joint working with the Royal Colleges and specialist societies.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-02T18:14:46.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454871/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454871/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Kidney Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that (a) the Think Kidneys programme, (b) ongoing work relating to acute kidney injury and (c) other work programmes being led by the National Clinical Director for Renal Disease for NHS England will continue to be taken forward following the discontinuance of that director's post.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","28334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454872","Department of Health","false","2016-03-03","<p>This information is not held centrally and is a matter for the local providers and commissioners.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS 111 commissioning standards issued in June 2014 state that all staff involved in handling NHS 111 calls must comply with the Licensing Requirements of the Clinical Decision Support Software used (NHS Pathways). Staff must also undertake training on: how to interact with urgent care services; the use of local Directories of Services; NHS Values; delivering excellent customer services; and safeguarding.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-03T16:29:46.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454872/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454872/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","NHS 111: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what training staff in (a) Lancashire and (b) the North West who handle NHS 111 calls receive other that the mandatory training covered by the NHS 111 Commissioning Standards.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","28247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454873","Department of Health","false","2016-03-01","<p>Individual healthcare providers are responsible for ensuring that they have the right level of staffing to provide high quality care to their patients.</p><p> </p><p>The following table taken from the monthly workforce statistics published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) shows the total consultant figures for May 2010, November 2010 and for November 2015 working in the National Health Service in England. The data for November 2015 is the latest available. The HSCIC statistics do not show cellular pathology, but data is provided for those working in the pathology group.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>England full-time equivalent</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>May 2010</p></td><td><p>November 2010</p></td><td><p>November 2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All Consultants</p></td><td><p>35,174</p></td><td><p>36,010</p></td><td><p>42,423</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Consultants in Pathology group</p></td><td><p>2,426</p></td><td><p>2,486</p></td><td><p>2,597</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Health and Social Care Information Centre NHS monthly workforce statistics</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-01T15:26:22.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454873/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454873/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the (a) scale of the difficulty experienced by trusts in recruiting to consultant posts and (b) effect of that difficulty on numbers of occupied consultant posts in cellular pathology.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","28248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454874","Home Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p>Border Force operates a multi-layered search regime using a range of interventions to screen all freight vehicles entering the UK through the juxtaposed ports.</p><p>This includes the use of specialist technologies such as Passive Millimetre Wave Imaging devices, heartbeat monitors and carbon dioxide detectors as well as physical searches by sniffer dogs, Border Force staff and specialist search contractors.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-29T15:59:31.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454874/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454874/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Large Goods Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many lorries were (a) routinely searched and (b) searched for illegal immigrants at English ports in each of the last three years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","28262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454875","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Chancellor the Exchequer announced the 2015 Spending Review to Parliament on 25th November 2015. Home Office ministers are in the process of allocating budgets for the next financial year to ensure that the department supports its key objectives of preventing terrorism, cutting crime and controlling immigration.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T16:29:39.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454875/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454875/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454875/answer/previousversion/47900","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Immigration Controls: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what additional funding she plans to commit to tackling illegal immigration; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","28263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454876","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government’s system-wide approach to tackling Organised Immigration Crime is based on information and intelligence from a wide variety of sources. The Government takes Organised Immigration Crime very seriously – we are working to smash the criminal gangs that are fuelling this terrible trade in people. In June 2015 the Prime Minister announced the creation of the Organised Immigration Crime Taskforce bringing together officers from the NCA, Border Force, Immigration Enforcement and the Crown Prosecution Service. The Taskforce was subsequently expanded in November 2015 to more than 100 officers, and has had its funding extended until 2020. The Government values the intelligence-led approach to tackling Organised Immigration Crime Europol helps to facilitate, including through Joint Operational Team Mare, and welcomes the launch by Europol on 22 February 2016 of the new European Migrant Smuggling Centre which will proactively support EU Member States in dismantling criminal networks involved in organised migrant smuggling. The UK has been at the forefront of calls in the EU for a robust approach to tackling Organised Immigration Crime.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T16:42:19.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454876/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454876/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the implications of the findings of the report by Europol, Migrant Smuggling in the EU, published in February 2016, for her policies on tackling smuggling through the criminal justice system.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","28297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454877","Home Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>We have seen an increase in the scale and pace of terrorist communications by groups like ISIL, encouraging vulnerable young people to travel to conflict zones like Syria and Iraq. This Government takes seriously the threat from online terrorist and extremist propaganda, which can directly influence people who are vulnerable to radicalisation.</p><p>Since 2010 over 140,000 pieces of terrorist-related material have been removed by industry from various online platforms at the request of the dedicated police Counter-Terrorism Internet Referral Unit (CTIRU). Approximately 55,000 removals were made in 2015 alone. Removal requests are now at over 1,000 a week and approximately 70% of CTIRU’s caseload is Daesh related.</p><p>We are pressing industry to take a lead in tackling the abuse of their services by terrorist and extremist groups.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-03-03T17:27:39.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454877/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454877/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454877/answer/previousversion/47907","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Terrorism: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many social media accounts promoting extremist content were recommended for closure by her Department in each of the last 12 months; and what proportion of such content related to Daesh.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","28422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454878","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Home Office works with its contractors, local authorities and the Strategic Migration Partnerships to ensure that impact of the dispersal of asylum seekers to local authorities is reviewed regularly. The Home Office was aware of the expansion of existing accommodation in East Cardiff. Decisions on the use of accommodation including which premises are used are made by the individual contractors, who bear the cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T17:29:36.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454878/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454878/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454878/answer/previousversion/47892","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Asylum: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department was informed of plans by Clearsprings to expand asylum accommodation into East Cardiff.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","28423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454879","Home Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Home Office has a rigorous contract compliance regime in place to ensure that the required performance standards expected of all providers, as defined in the contracts, are met. This includes monthly contract management and quarterly strategic review meetings, as well as regular daily discussions with COMPASS providers’ operational delivery managers about day to day issues. The Home Office investigates complaints it receives from service users and third parties and works with contractors to ensure that any issues raised are addressed promptly.</p><p>Performance against each key performance indicator (KPI) is measured and may, dependent upon the level of non-conformance, lead to the application of a KPI score. The overall/total score across all KPIs is then used to determine the value of Service Credit (rebate) which should be deducted from the monthly invoice. If an individual KPI is met, no score is accrued and no service credit applies. The following table indicates the amount of service credits recovered following KPI non-conformance for each of the COMPASS contracts from the start of the contracts.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-2016 (YTD)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Serco SNI</strong></p></td><td><p>£773, 792</p></td><td><p>£156,156</p></td><td><p>£443, 545</p></td><td><p><strong>£1,373,493</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Serco NW</strong></p></td><td><p>£3,137, 017</p></td><td><p>£1,974</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><strong>£3,138,991</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>G4S MEE</strong></p></td><td><p>£1,349, 475</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><strong>£1,349, 475</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>G4S NEYH</strong></p></td><td><p>£368, 107</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><strong>£368, 107</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CRH WSW</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CRH LSE</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£5,628, 391</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£158,130</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£443, 545</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£6,230,066</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-02T15:20:37.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454879/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454879/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454879/answer/previousversion/47904","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was levied in respect of service credits in each key performance indicator designated met in respect of each Compass region in each year from 2012-13 to 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","28212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454880","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government has a legal obligation to provide support to asylum applicants who would otherwise be destitute. Support is provided in form of subsistence allowance and accommodation. The Government provides funding for Strategic Migration Partnerships which act as a focal point for all local authorities in the relevant region to consider and resolve any issues relating to dispersals and migration. The funding for the North West Strategic Migration Partnership for 2015/16 was £139,216.</p><p>The Government also provides additional funding to local authorities to support Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children, those leaving care and asylum seekers who are turning 18. The total funding for this population in 2014/5 financial year for Manchester City Council was £441,113.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T16:31:16.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454880/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454880/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454880/answer/previousversion/47902","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Asylum: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what direct funding has been provided to local authorities in Greater Manchester to manage the community impact of asylum placements in those areas.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","28218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454881","Home Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government’s position is unchanged. The Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency has issued a marketing authorisation and the Home Office has amended the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 to enable Sativex to be available to patients via health care practitioners.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-29T15:51:02.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454881/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454881/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Cannabis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 26859, if she will update her Department's response to e-petition 104867, on legalisation of medicinal cannabis, in respect of the information on availability of the drug Sativex.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","28215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454882","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government does not confiscate the belongings of Syrian refugees or refugees of any other nationality to help meet the cost of their stay in the UK.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T16:43:27.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454882/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454882/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 28 January 2016 to Question 23729, what the Government's policy is on the confiscation of the belongings of Syrian refugees over a certain value to help meet the cost of their stay in the UK.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","28181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454883","Home Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>We are committed to tackling people trafficking and all forms of modern slavery. The Modern Slavery Act 2015 gives law enforcement agencies the tools they need to tackle modern slavery, ensures that perpetrators can receive suitably severe sentences up to life imprisonment, enhances support and protection for victims and places a duty on large businesses to report on what they are doing to stop modern slavery occurring in their global supply chains. We have successfully lobbied for the establishment of the first ever UN Sustainable Development Goal to end modern slavery and are working with a range of international partners to tackle slavery and its causes. We are also piloting a new approach to identifying and supporting potential victims of slavery through the National Referral Mechanism and we have appointed an Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner to spread best practice in the UK and overseas.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-02T15:26:20.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454883/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454883/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to counter people trafficking.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","28270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454884","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The police and Crown Prosecution Service work together to take decisions on whether to pursue a prosecution under the Protection from Harassment Act 1997, applying the evidential and public interest tests set out in the Code for Crown Prosecutors. The Code provides that prosecutors should have regard to whether the suspect is, or was at the time of the offence, suffering from any mental or ill health as, in some circumstances, this may mean that it is less likely that a prosecution is required.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-01T11:48:54.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454884/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454884/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-24","Harassment: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what account the police takes of mental health conditions when deciding whether to prosecute people under the Protection from Harassment Act 1997.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","28428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454885","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-02","<p>At the Supporting Syria and the Region Conference, the Prime Minister announced that the UK will more than double our total pledge to the Syria crisis from £1.12 billion to over £2.3 billion. This funding will support those in need inside Syria and in the surrounding region which is dealing with the impact of the crisis, including Jordan. Final country allocations are still being decided but it is clear that aid from the UK in Jordan will rise compared to previous years.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-02T16:58:31.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454885/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454885/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-24","Jordan: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will increase aid to Jordan in order to help that country cope with the inflow of Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","28175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454886","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>The UK recognises the terrible loss for Mzuzu University and academia in Malawi caused by the fire in December 2015 which destroyed the university library and its stock of 45,000 books.</p><p> </p><p>We commend the Scotland Malawi Partnership for coordinating efforts in Scotland to appeal for donations for the restocking and rebuilding of the library. Officials have met with the Scotland Malawi Partnership and the Mzuzu University Vice Chancellor to discuss possible funding opportunities. It is encouraging that Scottish Universities are again demonstrating Scotland’s unique people to people approach to supporting Malawi at a time when the country is also facing a humanitarian crisis and funding priorities are in strong competition.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-29T14:48:07.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454886/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454886/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-24","Malawi: Universities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will issue a response to EDM 1011, Fire at Mzuzu University, Malawi.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","28216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454887","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. The civil service works to support the government’s position.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-29T17:47:28.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454887/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454887/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-24","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has made to reallocate UK aid funding from cross-EU funds and programmes in the event of the UK voting to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","28421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454888","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>We welcome the outcome of the recent High Level Meeting of the OECD’s Development Assistance Committee (DAC), which agreed how the Official Development Assistance (ODA) rules should be updated to better tackle the pressing global development issues of the 21st century. The updates to the ODA rules both better recognise the detrimental impact that conflict, fragility and insecurity have on efforts to tackle poverty and reflect the importance of private sector investment for development.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-03-01T11:38:52.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454888/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454888/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-24","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has made an assessment of the potential effect of the change in the OECD definition of foreign aid to include some military spending on the effectiveness of aid spend on reducing poverty.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","28296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454889","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>The UK is assisting Fiji in response to Tropical Cyclone Winston. The UK makes core contributions to the UN Agencies, CERF, ECHO and the Red Cross, all of whom may contribute to the response. We are also contributing technical support to strengthen UNICEF’s capacity and are ready to consider further requests for humanitarian experts should it be required. DFID has also offered to provide support to the UN Disaster &amp; Coordination team and will remain in contact with Agencies in the region.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-03-01T11:38:28.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454889/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454889/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-24","Fiji: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if the Government will contribute emergency aid to Fiji and its surrounding islands following the recent cyclone.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","28295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454890","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>As set out in the Co-hosts’ Declaration from the Supporting Syria and the Region Conference (available at <a href="https://www.supportingsyria2016.com/media/" target="_blank">https://www.supportingsyria2016.com/media/</a>) donor funding will support plans set out in detailed Statements of Intent by refugee-hosting governments aimed at improving the investment climate and creating jobs for host communities and refugees from Syria.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-03-01T11:38:04.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454890/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454890/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-24","Middle East: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 15 February 2016 to Question 26161, how will the funds raised as result of the Supporting Syria Conference be used to create sustainable jobs in Levantine states with high youth unemployment.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","28294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454891","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-29","<p>The former probation trusts ceased operation on 31 May 2014, as part of the previous Government’s <em>Transforming Rehabilitation</em> reforms. The trusts’ archived records are now held by the National Offender Management Service.</p><p> </p><p>Within the specified timescale, it is not possible to ascertain whether or not the information requested is held in the archives. I will write to the hon. Member in due course to let him know the position and to provide the information if we have it.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-29T11:22:22.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454891/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454891/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-24","Staffordshire and West Midlands Probation Trust: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 7 January 2016 to Question 21452, how many jobs at the Staffordshire and West Midlands Probation Trust were abolished or relocated from Stoke-on Trent between May 2010 and 1 June 2014.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454892","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-04","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer for PQ 28151, answered on 18 March 2016. This can be found on the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-02-23/28151/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-02-23/28151/</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-04T15:14:09.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454892/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454892/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-24","Prisons: Discipline","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) disturbances and (b) riots have been recorded (i) on the prison estate and (ii) in private prisons since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454893","Department of Health","false","2016-03-03","<p>A search of the Department’s central correspondence system shows that the Department received 22 representations that made direct or indirect reference to the report `Surrogacy in the UK: Myth Busting and Reform' since it was published in November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has no current plans to change the legislation in respect of surrogacy arrangements.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","28366 ; 28369","2016-03-03T16:31:43.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454893/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454893/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-24","Surrogate Motherhood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to Surrogacy in the UK: Myth Busting and Reform, published in November 2015, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to reform the law governing surrogacy to better balance the rights of those involved and the welfare of children born via surrogacy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","28367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454894","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Government has made no such assessment. Parental orders provide a mechanism to enable a couple who have entered into a surrogacy arrangement to become that child’s legal parents. There is no obligation to obtain a parental order but a couple who commission a surrogacy arrangement are advised and encouraged to do so in order to achieve a recognisable transfer of parenthood in the UK. In deciding whether to exercise its discretion and award a Parental order, the court has regard to all the facts of the case and the overriding importance of the welfare of the child throughout their life.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-03-02T12:02:03.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454894/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454894/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-24","Surrogate Motherhood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effects on children and families of the parental orders procedure following surrogacy arrangements.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","28368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454895","Scotland Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-03-01T11:58:04.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454895/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454895/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-02-24","UK Membership of EU: Referendums: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what assessment he has made of the implications of a decision to leave the EU on provisions in the Scotland Act 1988 requiring compliance with EU law.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","28414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454896","Prime Minister","false","2016-02-29","<p>The arrangements for special advisers who wish to work for a campaign are set out in the Cabinet Secretary's letter of 23 February. It is not appropriate to publish personal data about individual special advisers.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-02-29T17:11:05.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454896/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454896/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-02-24","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what special advisers have (a) successfully and (b) unsuccessfully sought his permission to work on a EU referendum campaign.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454897","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government has been in regular contact with a wide range of stakeholders to maximise opportunities to meet our ambition to deliver one million more homes. The new Estate Regeneration Advisory Panel, Chaired by , my Noble Friend, the rt. hon. Lord Heseltine, comprises a range of experts and will provide advice on how the £140 million loan fund can best be utilised, in addition to other private and public funding sources. The fund was allocated in the Spending Review assessment.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-29T17:06:48.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454897/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454897/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-24","Housing Estates: Regeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Prime Minister's announcement of 10 January 2016 on sink estates, with what bodies he discussed the redevelopment of 100 sink estates; and on what grounds the sum of £140 million for that redevelopment was arrived at.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","28338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454898","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>There is currently no additional capacity for extra stations planned for East Cardiff within Network Rail’s current capital spending period (2014-2019).</p><p>However, I can confirm that the second round for the New Station Fund will begin in Spring 2016. The New Stations Fund is to provide funding for the construction of brand new or reopened stations that are promoted by third parties. £20 million will be available and local authorities who are interested are encouraged to submit bids for the funds.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-29T17:25:59.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454898/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454898/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what additional capacity for extra stations is planned for East Cardiff as a result of the electrification of the Great Western main line.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","28419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454899","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government remains committed to supporting the UK’s zero emission motorcycle industry. We have been working with stakeholders on the details of a scheme and will make a further announcement in due course.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:22:40.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454899/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454899/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Electric Vehicles: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to implement the policy announced on 27 March 2015 by the previous Government on funding to increase the uptake for electric two-wheeled vehicles.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454900","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-02","<p>Industrial relations within the transport industry are primarily managed by the service providers in that industry, e.g. the rail companies. The Department for Transport is committed to continuing to work constructively with the transport unions to deliver the best possible transport services. We will also develop and promote this Government’s trade union reforms as part of that relationship.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-02T11:22:23.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454900/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454900/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Transport: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what he plans his Department's policy on industrial relations with transport unions to be over the next three years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","28250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454901","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>This was a commercial matter for Network Rail. I understand that the total cost to Network Rail of acquiring the ownership of freight sites under Project Mountfield was £220 million.</p><p> </p><p>The overall revenue figure for 2014/15 was £5.2 million which represents a 5 month period – November to March – given the transfer of sites occurred in October 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail is forecasting this to grow to £16 million per annum by 2017 alongside realising significant operational efficiencies.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-29T17:30:45.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454901/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454901/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total cost to Network Rail was of acquiring the ownership of freight sites under Project Mountfield; and what overall revenue received by Network Rail from those sites in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","28302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454902","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>I have been informed by Network Rail that as of 26 February 2016, the total value of EU funding that has been awarded for the Great Western Mainline Electrification is € 11,085,000.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-29T17:33:24.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454902/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454902/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the value of EU funding was for the Great Western Main Line electrification programme on the most recent date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","28303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454903","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>Regional Safety Coordinators have now been appointed by Highways England. The first appointment was made in January 2016 and the final appointment was made this month.</p><p> </p><p>The killed and seriously injured reduction target, which is within the Roads Investment Strategy, is a 40% reduction by 2020 (against 2005 to 2009 average baseline). Highways England's Regional Incident and Casualty Reduction Plans which will provide the disaggregated targets per region will be published in April 2016.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:36:15.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454903/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454903/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Roads: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress Highways England has made on introducing Regional Road Safety Co-ordinators; and whether Highways England's Regional Incident and Casualty Reduction Plans will include targets for casualty reductions.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","28304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454904","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>This information is not held by the Department. This benefit is managed by the Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC), and they may have this information; they can be contacted at <a href="mailto:rstl@atoc.org" target="_blank">rstl@atoc.org</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-29T17:39:11.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454904/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454904/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","British Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many former employees of British Rail were entitled to receive Safeguarded Travel benefits on the most recent date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","28305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454905","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The annual funding grant paid to the Greater London Authority by the Department is not ring-fenced and it is a matter for the Mayor to determine how it is spent.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T14:04:29.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454905/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454905/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Cycling: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 15 February 2016 to Question 26407, what funding for cycling in London is included within the (a) £925 million of capital funding and (b) £659 million of resource funding paid to Transport for London.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454906","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>We are working with our European counterparts on specifications for safer and more aerodynamic cab designs in HGVs. We will continue to work pro-actively with the European Commission and other EU Member States, the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders (SMMT), Transport for London and other stakeholders to improve the safety of HGVs.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport’s “British Road Safety Statement” published in December 2015 sets out a number of measures to further improve safety of vehicles. The Department plans to consult on sideguard provisions in the second half of 2016 to ensure these important safety devices remain on the vehicle throughout its life.</p><p> </p><p>Department for Transport officials have negotiated improved requirements for mirrors on the passenger side of the largest heavy goods vehicles and these will apply from 1 July 2016. Camera monitoring systems will be permitted to replace mirrors from around 1 September 2016, which should further improve driver vision around HGVs.</p><p> </p><p>Officials have worked with our European partners to require fitment of technology helping HGVs avoid collisions. Electronic Stability Control (ESC) has been gradually rolled out to all new HGVs and the final phase will be implemented on 11 July 2016, when it will become compulsory on certain smaller HGVs below 12 tonnes laden weight. Advanced Emergency Braking Systems were recently made compulsory on new HGVs over 8 tonnes laden weight, and we expect it will become compulsory on goods vehicles between 3.5 and 8 tonnes laden weight from 1 November 2018.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-03T14:10:06.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454906/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454906/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Large Goods Vehicles: Design","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2016 to Question 25199, what steps he is taking to encourage the development and implementation of improved HGV design.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454907","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>The equalities impact assessment was published in 2010 and can be found at <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/adobepdf/165220-/cuts.pdf" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/adobepdf/165220-/cuts.pdf</a>.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:33:44.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454907/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454907/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 2 November 2010 to the Questions from the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish, Official Report, column 702W, on bus services: finance, if he will place in the Library a copy of the equalities impact assessment carried out by his Department of the decision to reduce the value of the Bus Service Operators Grant by 20 per cent.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","28238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454908","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-02","<p>Highways England is aware of the public hearing and has agreed to attend and give evidence.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-02T11:16:21.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454908/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454908/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","M6","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will direct Highways England to give evidence to the public hearing on 18 March 2016 organised by the West Midlands Police and Crime Commissioner into closures and delays on the M6 on 4 and 5 February 2016.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454909","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>The standards of integrity, impartiality and honesty are set out in Departmental policies and guidance, as well as being set out in the Civil Service Code which applies to all Civil Servants.</p><p> </p><p>The full text of the Civil Service Code can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/civil-service-code/the-civil-service-code" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/civil-service-code/the-civil-service-code</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-29T17:59:42.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454909/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454909/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Transport: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that transport trade unions retain confidence in his Department's Senior Civil Servants' impartiality.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","28208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454910","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department for Transport is committed to continuing to work constructively with the Transport Unions in the coming years to deliver the best possible transport services for all passengers, users and taxpayers.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-29T17:42:18.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454910/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454910/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Transport: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the comment by Peter Wilkinson, Director of Rail Passenger Services at his Department, of 22 February 2016, about future industrial relations between his Department and transport unions is accurate.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","28209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454911","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>We have been reviewing the Bus Service Operators Grant scheme in recent years with a view to improving its effectiveness in supporting bus services. In their assessment of the impact of any changes in policy associated with the Bus Service Operators’ Grant, departmental economists normally assume operators pass subsidy received on to passengers 50% through lower fares and 50% through increased service levels. Under these assumptions, they estimate that BSOG has the impact of keeping fares 3% lower than they would be in its absence in England outside of London.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","28184","2016-03-03T14:00:11.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454911/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454911/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on the relationship between the bus service operators grant and the cost of bus fares.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454912","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>We have been reviewing the Bus Service Operators Grant scheme in recent years with a view to improving its effectiveness in supporting bus services. In their assessment of the impact of any changes in policy associated with the Bus Service Operators’ Grant, departmental economists normally assume operators pass subsidy received on to passengers 50% through lower fares and 50% through increased service levels. Under these assumptions, they estimate that BSOG has the impact of keeping fares 3% lower than they would be in its absence in England outside of London.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","28183","2016-03-03T14:00:11.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454912/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454912/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of whether the bus service operators grant is used by bus operators to keep fares down.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","28184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454913","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Department for Transport carries out activities in Oversea Territories that feeds into the Overseas Development Aid. The Government published details of Overseas Development Aid at the Spending Review 2015 and further updates will be published in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-02T11:41:03.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454913/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454913/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-24","Department for Transport: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's spending was in Overseas Development Aid on (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) the first 10 months of 2015-16; and what the recipient countries of that aid were.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","28269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454914","Women and Equalities","false","2016-03-03","<p>The government wants all young people to be confident and positive about their body image. My department has worked with a range of bodies, including the Advertising Association and the National Citizen Service, to develop materials that support good practice and encourage young people to become more informed and resilient consumers of media content; and with the PSHE Association to provide guidance for teachers on teaching about body image using accredited resources.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","29287","2016-03-03T14:38:34.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454914/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454914/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-02-24","Disability: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to encourage body confidence in young disabled people.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","28172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454915","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department and Personal Independence Payment (PIP) Assessment Providers have robust audit and assurance regimes in place to check the quality and consistency of PIP assessments. These arrangements confirm that independent health professional advice complies with the required standards and that it is clear and medically reasonable. They also provide assurance that the assessment and opinion given are consistent so that, irrespective of where or by whom the assessment is carried out, claimants with conditions that have the same functional effect will ultimately receive the same benefit outcome.</p><p> </p><p>Regular meetings take place with Her Majesty’s Court and Tribunals Service to discuss PIP appeals; feedback is provided to Assessment Providers if there is any indication that the assessment is a factor in appeals or reapplications to inform continuous improvement activity.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-29T14:59:07.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454915/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454915/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Personal Independence Payment: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what analysis his Department conducts of personal independence payment medical assessments to (a) help identify common issues which cause repeated appeals and reapplications and (b) ensure a consistent approach across such assessments.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","28329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454916","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-02","<p>All health professionals receive comprehensive training in disability analysis which includes a functional evaluation as to how medical conditions and the long-term medical treatment of those conditions affect an individual’s ability to perform day-to-day activities. Prior to carrying out an assessment they routinely refresh their knowledge of any condition with which they are not fully familiar.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-02T10:34:28.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454916/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454916/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Personal Independence Payment: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what training and guidance is provided to medical assessors who examine claimants for personal independence payment on the implications of (a) dialysis and (b) other long-term medical treatments for such claimants.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","28330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454917","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-29","<p>These are issues to be answered as part of the implementation process.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-29T15:27:59.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454917/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454917/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Social Security Benefits: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the (a) time taken to introduce and (b) cost of introduction of a system of in-work benefits for newly-arrived EU nationals as envisaged in Section D of the Decision of the Heads of State or Government, meeting within the European Council, on 18 and 19 February 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","28382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454918","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-29","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-29T12:05:11.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454918/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454918/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Housing Benefit: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of how many people in supported housing specifically designated for (a) disabled people, (b) victims of domestic violence, (c) people with substance misuse problems and (d) others will be affected by the change in housing benefit to the Shared Accommodation Rate.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","28324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454919","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-03","<p>Advance payments of up to 50% of their Universal Credit award are available to all new Universal Credit claimants who are in financial need.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-03T15:41:01.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454919/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454919/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department provides to (a) claimants of universal credit while the benefit is assessed and dispatched and (b) people becoming unemployed from low-paid and temporary jobs who have no redundancy payments or other income.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","28272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454920","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department has four contracts with Hewlett Packard Enterprise: Application Development and Application Maintenance &amp; Support – these two contracts expired on 29/02/2016 and an extension has been agreed to 28/02/2018. Hosting – this contract runs till 23/02/2018. Desktop – this contract runs till 08/01/2017. DWP future contracting plans are commercially sensitive. The Department is progressing its strategy to deliver its technology requirements, and this includes both in-house services, and externally provided services sourced through procurement exercises using open competitions under the EU Procurement Directives and call-off competitions under Government Frameworks.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-29T16:15:17.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454920/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454920/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Department for Work and Pensions: Hewlett-Packard","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the end-dates are of his Department's contracts with Hewlett Packard Enterprise; which such contracts he plans to extend, for what reasons and to what dates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","28320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454921","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department anticipates a shift in the way in which citizens will engage with the Department - with greater digital interaction in the future. Digital Technology, Data and Security capabilities are a key enabler of this shift. The Department is progressing its strategy to deliver the underpinning technology requirements, and this includes both in-house services and externally provided services through procurement exercises using open competitions under the EU Procurement Directives and call-off competitions under Government Frameworks, such as GCloud and Crown Hosting.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-29T16:06:55.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454921/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454921/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Department for Work and Pensions: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's plans are for the delivery of IT and digital services after the end dates of current contracts.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","28321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454922","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-29","<p>So far representations have been made by 93 individuals and 16 housing providers about the proposed change of social sector housing benefit to the level of local housing allowance.</p><p> </p><p>DWP Ministers and officials will continue to have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","28323","2016-02-29T12:00:49.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454922/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454922/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have made representations to his Department about the proposed change of social sector housing benefit to the level of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","28322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454923","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-29","<p>So far representations have been made by 93 individuals and 16 housing providers about the proposed change of social sector housing benefit to the level of local housing allowance.</p><p> </p><p>DWP Ministers and officials will continue to have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","28322","2016-02-29T12:00:49.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454923/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454923/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many housing providers made representations to his Department about the proposed change of social sector housing benefit to the level of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","28323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454924","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-03","<p>We have fully assessed the impacts on equality of the welfare measures in the Bill and the wider budget, meeting our obligations as set out in the Public Sector Equality Duty. An impact assessment was published on 20 July last year.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-03T17:05:42.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454924/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454924/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-24","Employment and Support Allowance: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of changes to employment and support allowance for new claimants in the work-related activity group on the mental health of those affected.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","28273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454925","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>The seven Research Councils currently operate their own corporate functions, with separate Human Resources, Finance, Communications and IT operations.</p><p>The Research Councils are working with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on a new digital grants system and common technology platform.</p><p>The Research Councils share a number of services including a main campus in Swindon at Polaris House; access to the London base of the Medical Research Council (MRC); and Internal Audit and Assurance functions, which are hosted by the Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC). BBSRC also operate the estates and facilities management of Polaris House.</p><p>All seven Councils have their transactional HR, finance, payroll, systems and grants administration provided by UK Shared Business Services and six of the seven Councils share a pension scheme and its administration, with MRC running its own pension scheme.</p><p>The Government is implementing Sir Paul Nurse’s report, which recommended an evolution of the Research Councils into a formal organisation with a single Accounting Officer. Sir Paul advised that a new Research UK body could support the whole system to collectively become more than the sum of its parts, including by simplifying transactional operations, reducing the burden of administration currently placed on each individual Research Council, and enabling a stronger focus on multi-disciplinary research. We also want to strengthen collaboration between the research base and the commercialisation of discoveries in the business community and this is why we are looking to integrate Innovate UK into Research UK. Innovate UK will retain its clear business focus and separate funding stream.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-16T15:38:11.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454925/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454925/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-24","Research Councils: Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what (a) human resources, (b) communications, (c) grant administration, (d) building and estates management and (e) other administrative functions are shared by the seven research councils; and which such services are delivered independently by each research council.","false","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","28358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454926","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-08","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. We are currently working on improving the data collected on grants through the development of an internal Government Grants Information System. The clause will apply to all grants except in exceptional circumstances as set out at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/government-grants-register" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/government-grants-register</a>.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-08T11:48:38.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454926/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454926/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-24","Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will estimate how many (a) people and (b) organisations will be affected by the interim guidance on the new anti-lobbying clause in government grant agreements.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454927","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>Nickel has been used in UK coinage for over 60 years and nickel-plated coins introduced in the UK in 2012 were already in use in Canada, New Zealand and other countries around the world.</p><p> </p><p>Independent tests have concluded that there is no increased risk to people from handling the nickel-plated steel five pence and ten pence coins compared to coins made of cupronickel alloy.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T16:48:18.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454927/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454927/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Coinage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Swedish government over their decision to end the production of coins containing nickel; whether he plans to further investigate the health risks posed to those who suffer from nickel allergy of the decision to switch to steel nickel-plated 5p and 10p coins in 2012; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","28293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454928","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong>400,000 couples have successfully claimed Marriage Allowance. HM Revenue and Customers is continuing to extensively market Marriage Allowance, including through print, radio and billboard advertising. Eligible couples who haven’t already claimed for the tax year 2015/16 will not lose out as they have until 5 April 2020 to do so. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-03T17:05:25.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454928/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454928/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-24","Married People: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the uptake of the marriage tax allowance is; what steps he is taking to increase uptake of that allowance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","28276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454929","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-03","<p>The cost of the Defence Assistance Fund in financial year 2014-15 was £15.529 million.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-03-03T16:09:22.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454929/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454929/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Defence Assistance Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to the public purse of the Defence Assistance Fund was in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","28398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454930","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Export Support Team is part of the Defence and Security Organisation, part of UK Trade and Investment. The Minister for Trade and Investment is responsible for administrative and funding arrangements, including attached Service personnel's capitation costs. Therefore, there is no cost to the Ministry of Defence.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-02T16:24:12.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454930/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454930/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to his Department of the Export Support Team was in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15; and whether those costs have been reimbursed by the UK Trade and Investment Defence and Security Organisation.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","28396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454931","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-02","<p>The following information shows Ministry of Defence funding for the Defence Attaché and Advisor Network for financial year (FY) 2013-14 and FY 2014-15.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2014-15 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Attaché Costs </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£31,864,185</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£31,635,761</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>FCO Platform Charges</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£9,919,278</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£13,302,918</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total Cost </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£41,783,463</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£44,938,679</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Support for exports is one of the many roles carried out by Defence Attachés as part of the International Defence Engagement Strategy. The Defence Attaché network has no specific budget or post allocated to this task.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-03-02T16:21:25.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454931/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454931/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-24","Military Attachés","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost was of maintaining the defence attaché network in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15; and what proportion of the cost of that network was attributable to support for defence and security exports.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","28397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454932","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>Details of the Secretary of State’s international travel, including cost to the public purse, is published on a quarterly basis. International travel that has taken place since October 2015 will be published in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:54:18.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454932/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454932/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Department for Education: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what official foreign visits she has undertaken since 1 October 2015; and what the cost to the public purse was of those visits.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","28257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454933","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>The School Admissions Code contains a range of statutory provisions relating to school admission arrangements and to the wider admissions process. The code includes provisions to ensure that children of UK service personnel are not disadvantaged when applying for a school place. The role of the Schools Adjudicator is to consider objections about admission arrangements only. Some of the provisions in the code, therefore, do not fall within the adjudicator’s jurisdiction. There is no body which has jurisdiction to consider objections relating to these other provisions, but admission authorities must comply with all the statutory provisions in the code and, where they fail to do so, the Secretary of State has powers under section 496 and 497 of the Education Act 1996 to require them to comply.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-03T10:51:15.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454933/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454933/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-24","Armed Forces Covenant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 24 February 2016 to Question 27540, under whose jurisdiction objections citing provisions relating to the Armed Forces Covenant excluding those relating to service premium admission would fall.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","28355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454934","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-03","<p>In line with government policy, DECC is introducing the new anti-lobbying clause mandated by the Cabinet Office. DECC has previously included a prohibition on use of the grant for activities of a political or exclusively religious nature, and DECC is not aware of any breaches of this condition, although no investigation has been carried out. Most DECC grants are awarded to cover specified costs incurred by the grant recipient in undertaking a particular project and are paid to reimburse those costs on receipt of satisfactory evidence that the relevant costs have been incurred.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-03T15:53:50.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454934/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454934/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many organisations in receipt of grant funding awarded by her Department were found to have engaged in activity that influenced or attempted to influence Parliament, government, or the European Commission, or were found to have attempted to influence legislative or regulatory action in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","28292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454935","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-04","<p>The organisations that have received grant funding from DECC in FY2012-13, 2013-14 and 2014-15 are summarised in the attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-04T15:01:00.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454935/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454935/answer","WPQ 28359 Organisations and DECC public grant funding.pdf","WPQ 28359 Organisations and DECC public grant funding.pdf","Orgs receiving DECC public grant funding 2012-15","Orgs receiving DECC public grant funding 2012-15","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454935/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, which organisations have received public grant funding from her Department in each of the last three years; and what the purposes of each grant were.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","28359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454936","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Contracts for Difference (CfD) scheme allows a wide range of renewable technologies to compete for contracts.</p><p> </p><p>On 18 November 2015, my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change announced the intention to run three more auctions this Parliament, with the first, for the less established group of technologies that includes Offshore Wind, Wave, Tidal Stream, Advanced Conversion Technologies, Anaerobic Digestion, Dedicated Biomass with Combined Heat and Power (CHP) and Geothermal, planned for late 2016.</p><p> </p><p>We will announce plans for Pot 1 (established technologies) and Pot 3 (biomass conversion) in due course.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-01T13:10:51.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454936/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454936/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she has taken to ensure that all renewables can compete on equal terms in the additional rounds of renewable subsidy auctions scheduled between now and 2020.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","28360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454937","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-29","<p>DECC officials have met with local biomass generators and developers. There are several biomass projects at different stages of development around Immingham, Hull and Stallingborough. The £162million investment at the Brigg Renewable Energy Plant, a 40 MW straw fired biomass plant, has recently opened.</p><p> </p><p>Biomass generation is contributing jobs to Humberside. As a result of £100million in investment, the Humber International Terminal (HIT) at the Port of Immingham is already receiving some of the world’s largest shipments of biomass, destined for Drax, in the adjacent county of North Yorkshire. Drax is supported by the Renewables Obligation and has secured a Contract for Difference to convert another unit to biomass (under the Final Investment Decision enabling Renewables programme). If State Aid approval for the contract is obtained, the Humber will see some 6 million tonnes per annum of pellets imported into the UK. This will enhance its position for future business, including in the heat sector. The UK government continue to support Drax with the State Aid case.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-29T14:55:09.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454937/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454937/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-24","Biofuels: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she has taken to support the Humber region's biomass projects.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","28361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454938","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-29","<p>Natural England made two formal responses to Christchurch and East Dorset Council authority about the proposed housing at Marsh Lane which are attached</p><p>Subsequently we provided Dorset County Council (DCC) with advice on the proposed New Christchurch Primary School in relation to the Habitats Regulations Assessment undertaken by DCC. Our response is also attached.</p><p>Planning documents related to the New Christchurch Primary School, Marsh Lane, Christchurch, Dorset, BH23 2NH (8/15/0665) can be accessed via this link: <a href="http://countyplanning.dorsetforyou.com/ePlanningOPS/" target="_blank">http://countyplanning.dorsetforyou.com/ePlanningOPS/</a>.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-29T16:53:13.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454938/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454938/answer","8_15_0665 Christchurch Primary School lett 2.pdf ; CS_PSub_PCha_Response_CN3 NE.pdf ; Policy CN 3 Marsh Lane.pdf","8_15_0665 Christchurch Primary School lett 2.pdf ; CS_PSub_PCha_Response_CN3 NE.pdf ; Policy CN 3 Marsh Lane.pdf","PQ 28405 - Letter to Christchurch Primary School ; PQ 28405 - Marsh Lane ; PQ 28405 - Marsh Lane","PQ 28405 - Letter to Christchurch Primary School ; PQ 28405 - Marsh Lane ; PQ 28405 - Marsh Lane","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454938/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-24","Green Belt: Christchurch","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will place in the Library a copy of the representations which Natural England made in response to the (a) proposal in the draft Christchurch local plan for housing development on green belt land at Marsh Lane, Christchurch, and (b) planning application by Dorset County Council for a