"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454077","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-26","<p>The European Regional Development Fund does not provide funding to pupils.</p><p>The total investment for the Fund 2000-06 programme period in the North West was equivalent to just under £1.5 billion.</p><p>The figures for the 2007-13 European Regional Developement Fund programme, where investment commenced in 2009, are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Annual expenditure (£m)</p></td><td><p>Cumulative expenditure (£m)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>168.2</p></td><td><p>168.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>56.3</p></td><td><p>224.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>63.2</p></td><td><p>287.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>60.8</p></td><td><p>348.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>81.2</p></td><td><p>429.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>123.8</p></td><td><p>553.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>56.9</p></td><td><p>610.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-26T14:30:26.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454077/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454077/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","European Regional Development Fund: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many pupils in the North West have received funding from the European Regional Development Fund; and what the total investment from that fund in that region has been in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","28127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454078","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-26","<p>I have nothing to add to my earlier reply.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-26T14:31:14.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454078/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454078/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Multiple Occupation: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 11 February 2016 to Question 26305; what estimate his Department has made of the total number of licenses granted for houses of multiple occupation which are in use in (a) Coventry, (b) the West Midlands and (c) England in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","28054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454079","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>We announced on 13 October 2015 that the permitted development right for the change of use from office to residential is to be made permanent, and that those with prior approval will have three years from the date of prior approval in which to change use. Further information on the detail and timing of the regulations will be provided in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-29T17:29:50.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454079/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454079/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Change of Use","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 11 November 2015 to Question 15112, when he intends to bring forward amendments to the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) (England) Order 2015; what provisions will apply to office premises that have been granted prior approval for conversion to residential use but which will not be completed before 30 May 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","28026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454080","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Department has a health and wellbeing strategy that reflects the wider Civil Service priorities of mental health, musculoskeletal disorders and promoting a healthy lifestyle.</p><p>An effective Occupational Health and Workplace Adjustment services, together with an Employee Assistance Programme, are in place. The Department has committed and strong staff networks, including a Health and Wellbeing network.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:18:57.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454080/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454080/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Department for Communities and Local Government: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his Department's wellness strategy is.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454081","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my rt. hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office (Matthew Hancock) today, PQ 27946.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:08:56.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454081/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454081/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Department for Communities and Local Government: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the (a) policy and (b) other responsibilities are of each special adviser in his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454082","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-01","<p>The most recent local authority data held by the Department for Communities and Local Government is the estimated position for financial year 2015-16. Local authorities have estimated that their reserve balances as at 31 March 2016 will be as follows:</p><p>Ringfenced school reserves £2,213.16 million</p><p>Ringfenced public health reserves £138.83 million</p><p>Non ringfenced other earmarked reserves £13,396.76 million</p><p>Non ringfenced unallocated reserves £3,736.79 million</p><p>Full details can be found on the department’s webpage <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2015-to-2016-individual-local-authority-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2015-to-2016-individual-local-authority-data</a></p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-01T17:10:46.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454082/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454082/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the balances held by all English local authorities.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","27847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454083","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Spending Review underlined the priority this Government attaches to our ambition to build a million homes this Parliament and to double the number of new homeowners. Building on the successful contribution the Homes and Communities Agency made in the last Parliament, the Review will ensure that they are well-placed to deliver the Government’s objectives.</p><p>In line with Cabinet Office guidance, the Review will consider a range of options in looking at how the Agency can operate in the most effective and efficient way.</p><p>We will be seeking evidence from a wide range of sources, including the Agency itself, and will provide an opportunity for interested stakeholders to contribute views. Once this evidence has been collected and conclusions drawn, the Review will report as soon as possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","27314 ; 27315 ; 27316","2016-02-29T17:22:20.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454083/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454083/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Homes and Communities Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Written Statement of 10 February 2016, HCWS520, when he expects the Review of the Homes and Communities Agency to be published.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","27884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454084","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>Local authorities are best placed to understand the housing needs in their area. We expect them to work closely with key partners and their local communities in deciding what type of housing is needed.</p><p>National policy sets out clearly the need for local authorities to plan for the housing needs of all members of the community and that planning should encourage accessibility. The introduction of optional requirements for accessibility in the Building Regulations provides local authorities with the tools needed to ensure that new homes are accessible and that in particular the needs of disabled people are met.</p><p>Local authorities are held accountable for their housing delivery via their Local Plans which are tested by local independent planning inspectors and are scrutinised via yearly Authority Monitoring reports which set out progress on delivery against Local Plan targets. In addition local authorities must determine individual decisions in line with the development plan and other material considerations, such as the National Planning Policy Framework and having regard to viability considerations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","27876","2016-03-02T17:14:32.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454084/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454084/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had on introducing new duties on local authorities to assess the level of need for wheelchair accessible homes and set appropriate targets in local development plans.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","27874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454085","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>Starter Homes like all new homes, will ahve to meet Building Regulations' access requirements which ensure reasonable provision for people to gain access to and use, the dwelling and its facilities.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:19:58.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454085/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454085/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the proportion of starter homes that will be wheelchair accessible.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","27875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454086","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>Local authorities are best placed to understand the housing needs in their area. We expect them to work closely with key partners and their local communities in deciding what type of housing is needed.</p><p>National policy sets out clearly the need for local authorities to plan for the housing needs of all members of the community and that planning should encourage accessibility. The introduction of optional requirements for accessibility in the Building Regulations provides local authorities with the tools needed to ensure that new homes are accessible and that in particular the needs of disabled people are met.</p><p>Local authorities are held accountable for their housing delivery via their Local Plans which are tested by local independent planning inspectors and are scrutinised via yearly Authority Monitoring reports which set out progress on delivery against Local Plan targets. In addition local authorities must determine individual decisions in line with the development plan and other material considerations, such as the National Planning Policy Framework and having regard to viability considerations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","27874","2016-03-02T17:14:32.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454086/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454086/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he has taken to ensure that local authorities meet their obligation under the National Planning Policy Framework to meet the housing needs of disabled people requiring wheelchair accessible homes.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","27876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454087","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Government provides direct funding for specialised housing for older and disabled people through the Care and Support Specialised Housing Fund and the Affordable Homes Programme, making available up to £800 million for specialised housing for older, disabled, and vulnerable people over the next five years, which will deliver over 15,000 specialised homes.</p><p>The Government is also putting more money into the Disabled Facilities Grant to enable older and disabled people to live independently and safely in their own homes for longer. On top of the £1 billion the Government has invested in the grant since 2010, the grant will increase year on year for the next five years rising to over £500 million by 2020. In 2016-17 the Disabled Facilities Grant will grow to £394 million, a 79% increase on the current year.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","27872","2016-03-02T17:24:38.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454087/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454087/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to increase the supply of wheelchair accessible homes in the social and affordable housing sector.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","27870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454088","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Government has published data on the housing need of older and disabled people in England to support local authorities in assessing likely need in their local area. This can be found at link:https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-regulations-guide-to-available-disability-data</p><p>It is for local authorities to determine specific needs in their local areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:21:15.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454088/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454088/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of people requiring wheelchair accessible homes in (a) Easington, (b) the North East and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","27871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454089","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Government provides direct funding for specialised housing for older and disabled people through the Care and Support Specialised Housing Fund and the Affordable Homes Programme, making available up to £800 million for specialised housing for older, disabled, and vulnerable people over the next five years, which will deliver over 15,000 specialised homes.</p><p>The Government is also putting more money into the Disabled Facilities Grant to enable older and disabled people to live independently and safely in their own homes for longer. On top of the £1 billion the Government has invested in the grant since 2010, the grant will increase year on year for the next five years rising to over £500 million by 2020. In 2016-17 the Disabled Facilities Grant will grow to £394 million, a 79% increase on the current year.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","27870","2016-03-02T17:24:38.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454089/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454089/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Social Rented Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to help the social housing sector maintain and increase the provision of specialist accessible and adapted housing stock for people with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","27872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454090","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>In 2015 the Government updated planning policy and Building Regulations to support local authorities in meeting the housing needs of disabled and older people in their communities. This included the introduction of two optional levels of accessibility in the Building Regulations, Category 2 – Accessible and adaptable dwellings, and Category 3 – Wheelchair user dwellings which local authorities can apply to new development in their local area subject to needs and viability assessments.</p><p>These new options work as planning conditions to planning applications. Accessibility needs are met by each project’s own finance, be it for public, social or private homes. Some adaptations by individuals are eligible for funding through disabled facilities grants.</p><p>Accessibility to buildings has always been central to Approved Document M and greater concern and detail has been worked in since Disability Discrimination Act regulations 1995, 2005 and with the Equality Act 2010. Each update of Approved Document M further embeds government commitment to inclusivity and accessibility in guidance.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-03-02T17:07:45.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454090/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454090/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he has taken to secure the adequate supply of accessible homes suitable for disabled people.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","27873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454091","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-26","<p>Statutory Harbour Authorities (some of which are Local Authorities) have powers to deal with wrecks and unservicable and abandoned vessels within their harbour limits.</p><p> </p><p>These powers are available under sections 52, 56 and 57 of the Harbours, Docks and Piers Clauses Act 1847 (exercisable by the Harbour Master) and in section 252 of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995. The powers allow the removal of wrecks and unserviceable and abandoned vessels and recovery of the cost of doing so from the owner or through disposal of the vessel.</p><p> </p><p>Where there is no statutory harbour authority or conservancy authority in place to use the powers in the Merchant Shipping Act 1995, under s253 of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 the General Lighthouse Authority may use the same powers set out in section 252 to deal with such vessels where, in the authority’s opinion the vessel is, or is likely to become, an obstruction or danger to navigation or to lifeboats engaged in lifeboat service.</p><p> </p><p>The receiver of wreck, who only deals with wrecked vessels and is a statutory appointment under the Merchant Shipping Act 1995, has powers under section 243 of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 to dispose of unclaimed wrecks one year after they come into the receiver’s possession. The Act sets out the dissemination of the proceeds of sale after disposal expenses.</p><p> </p><p>Statutory Harbour Authorities operate on a commercial basis without ongoing support from Government and the General Lighthouse Authority are fully funded from a tax on shipping, receiving no money from the UK exchequer. There are no plans for any other funding to be made available.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","27908","2016-02-26T12:10:34.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454091/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454091/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-23","Boats: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what powers are available to (a) parish, (b) district and (c) county councils to dispose of abandoned boats in coastal areas; and whether a disposal cost recovery scheme exists for such disposals.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","27909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454092","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The attached table shows the number of S78 planning appeals that have been recovered over the last decade.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:38:12.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454092/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454092/answer","PQ 27886.docx","PQ 27886.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454092/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Planning Permission: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, on how many occasions in each year since 2009-10 he has directed that a planning application appeal which would otherwise be determined by a person appointed by the Secretary of State will instead be determined by the Secretary of State, using his powers under Schedule 6, Paragraph 3 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454093","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The attached table only covers Section 79 (1)(a) and Section 79(1)(b).</p><p>We do not hold the data on section 79(6) as the legislation is very rarely used with only a handful of cases in the last 7 years. In addition, the Section 79 (6) ‘compensation’ element only allows for a party to apply for costs. This can only occur where a party has behaved unreasonably, and this has directly caused another party to incur unnecessary or wasted expense. The costs order states the broad extent of the expense the party can recover from the party against whom the award is made. It does not determine the actual amount. PPG ‘Appeals’ section 4 relates.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:23:19.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454093/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454093/answer","PQ 27887.docx","PQ 27887.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454093/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-23","Planning Permission: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many appeals against Local Planning Authority decisions by developers he has received under Section 78 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 in each year since 2009-10; in how many of those cases in each year did he exercise his powers under Section 79 of that Act to (a) allow under Section 79(1)(a), (b) dismiss under Section 79(1)(b), (c) decline to determine under Section 79(6), (d) dismiss under Section 79(6A) the appeal and (e) amend the planning authority's original decision in any way; and in how many such cases the Local Planning Authority subsequently paid compensation to the developer as a result of his decision.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454094","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-26","<p>Statutory Harbour Authorities (some of which are Local Authorities) have powers to deal with wrecks and unservicable and abandoned vessels within their harbour limits.</p><p> </p><p>These powers are available under sections 52, 56 and 57 of the Harbours, Docks and Piers Clauses Act 1847 (exercisable by the Harbour Master) and in section 252 of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995. The powers allow the removal of wrecks and unserviceable and abandoned vessels and recovery of the cost of doing so from the owner or through disposal of the vessel.</p><p> </p><p>Where there is no statutory harbour authority or conservancy authority in place to use the powers in the Merchant Shipping Act 1995, under s253 of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 the General Lighthouse Authority may use the same powers set out in section 252 to deal with such vessels where, in the authority’s opinion the vessel is, or is likely to become, an obstruction or danger to navigation or to lifeboats engaged in lifeboat service.</p><p> </p><p>The receiver of wreck, who only deals with wrecked vessels and is a statutory appointment under the Merchant Shipping Act 1995, has powers under section 243 of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 to dispose of unclaimed wrecks one year after they come into the receiver’s possession. The Act sets out the dissemination of the proceeds of sale after disposal expenses.</p><p> </p><p>Statutory Harbour Authorities operate on a commercial basis without ongoing support from Government and the General Lighthouse Authority are fully funded from a tax on shipping, receiving no money from the UK exchequer. There are no plans for any other funding to be made available.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","27909","2016-02-26T12:10:34.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454094/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/r